WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.470 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:02.470 --> 00:00:04.446 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:04.446 --> 00:00:07.410 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:07.410 --> 00:00:10.582 align:middle line:90%


00:00:10.582 --> 00:00:11.540 align:middle line:90%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Hello?

00:00:11.540 --> 00:00:14.000 align:middle line:90%
Can people hear me in the back?

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:16.590 align:middle line:90%
Are we good?

00:00:16.590 --> 00:00:19.440 align:middle line:84%
So welcome to the
last lecture of 604--

00:00:19.440 --> 00:00:22.220 align:middle line:90%
no, 6.1200.

00:00:22.220 --> 00:00:23.510 align:middle line:90%
I'm totally sane.

00:00:23.510 --> 00:00:26.070 align:middle line:84%
I can remember which
class I'm teaching.

00:00:26.070 --> 00:00:26.570 align:middle line:90%
Welcome.

00:00:26.570 --> 00:00:27.630 align:middle line:84%
You made it through
the semester.

00:00:27.630 --> 00:00:28.130 align:middle line:90%
Well done.

00:00:28.130 --> 00:00:30.840 align:middle line:90%


00:00:30.840 --> 00:00:39.590 align:middle line:84%
So for today's material,
we are going to wrap up

00:00:39.590 --> 00:00:41.310 align:middle line:90%
our discussion of probability.

00:00:41.310 --> 00:00:45.030 align:middle line:84%
And in particular, we will
be discussing tail bounds.

00:00:45.030 --> 00:00:49.368 align:middle line:84%
So what happens if you
have a random variable?

00:00:49.368 --> 00:00:51.410 align:middle line:84%
What is the probability
that this random variable

00:00:51.410 --> 00:00:54.590 align:middle line:84%
is very large or very
small, very different

00:00:54.590 --> 00:00:58.262 align:middle line:90%
from its expectation?

00:00:58.262 --> 00:01:00.685 align:middle line:84%
So let's start with
a bit of a review.

00:01:00.685 --> 00:01:05.580 align:middle line:90%


00:01:05.580 --> 00:01:06.080 align:middle line:90%
Variance.

00:01:06.080 --> 00:01:08.870 align:middle line:90%


00:01:08.870 --> 00:01:12.860 align:middle line:84%
So I think we saw
from the last--

00:01:12.860 --> 00:01:14.510 align:middle line:84%
not last lecture,
two lectures ago,

00:01:14.510 --> 00:01:21.530 align:middle line:84%
possibly, so the variance
of a random variable R

00:01:21.530 --> 00:01:28.460 align:middle line:84%
is defined to be
the expectation of R

00:01:28.460 --> 00:01:30.770 align:middle line:84%
minus the expectation
of R squared.

00:01:30.770 --> 00:01:39.860 align:middle line:90%


00:01:39.860 --> 00:01:42.680 align:middle line:84%
And the standard deviation is
just the square root of that.

00:01:42.680 --> 00:01:45.570 align:middle line:84%
If you've taken stats
or anything like that,

00:01:45.570 --> 00:01:47.930 align:middle line:84%
that's probably
something that you've

00:01:47.930 --> 00:01:51.290 align:middle line:90%
seen more often than variance.

00:01:51.290 --> 00:01:54.780 align:middle line:84%
Another, not a definition,
but another useful formula,

00:01:54.780 --> 00:01:59.660 align:middle line:84%
an equivalent formulation of
this, is that the variance of R

00:01:59.660 --> 00:02:05.720 align:middle line:84%
is also equal to the
expectation of R squared

00:02:05.720 --> 00:02:13.460 align:middle line:84%
minus the square of the
expectation of R. So

00:02:13.460 --> 00:02:15.240 align:middle line:84%
not the definition,
but it's equivalent.

00:02:15.240 --> 00:02:19.730 align:middle line:84%
And I think in recitation
perhaps, you proved this.

00:02:19.730 --> 00:02:22.520 align:middle line:84%
This formula is a
particularly useful one

00:02:22.520 --> 00:02:24.145 align:middle line:84%
for what we're going
to be doing today.

00:02:24.145 --> 00:02:27.450 align:middle line:90%


00:02:27.450 --> 00:02:30.410 align:middle line:84%
We also saw that
variance is linear,

00:02:30.410 --> 00:02:33.090 align:middle line:90%
subject to certain constraints.

00:02:33.090 --> 00:02:37.060 align:middle line:84%
Does anybody remember what you
need for variance to be linear?

00:02:37.060 --> 00:02:39.800 align:middle line:90%


00:02:39.800 --> 00:02:40.882 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:02:40.882 --> 00:02:41.840 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Independence.

00:02:41.840 --> 00:02:44.492 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN:
Independence, OK.

00:02:44.492 --> 00:02:55.920 align:middle line:84%
So if you have R1, R2,
Rn are independent,

00:02:55.920 --> 00:03:01.356 align:middle line:84%
then the variance of the sum
is the sum of the variances--

00:03:01.356 --> 00:03:08.790 align:middle line:90%


00:03:08.790 --> 00:03:09.290 align:middle line:90%
oops.

00:03:09.290 --> 00:03:19.340 align:middle line:90%


00:03:19.340 --> 00:03:20.626 align:middle line:90%
Is that the right constraint?

00:03:20.626 --> 00:03:25.130 align:middle line:90%


00:03:25.130 --> 00:03:28.310 align:middle line:90%
Is it correct?

00:03:28.310 --> 00:03:31.970 align:middle line:90%
Who believes the statement?

00:03:31.970 --> 00:03:33.016 align:middle line:90%
Who disbelieves?

00:03:33.016 --> 00:03:35.690 align:middle line:90%


00:03:35.690 --> 00:03:37.940 align:middle line:90%
Who's still asleep?

00:03:37.940 --> 00:03:40.790 align:middle line:84%
Oh, OK, maybe we'll
give it a few minutes

00:03:40.790 --> 00:03:41.710 align:middle line:90%
for people to wake up.

00:03:41.710 --> 00:03:45.260 align:middle line:90%


00:03:45.260 --> 00:03:48.740 align:middle line:84%
Well, this is a
correct statement.

00:03:48.740 --> 00:03:53.030 align:middle line:84%
However, there is
something slightly stronger

00:03:53.030 --> 00:03:54.030 align:middle line:90%
that we can say.

00:03:54.030 --> 00:03:56.230 align:middle line:90%
We can weaken this condition.

00:03:56.230 --> 00:03:57.868 align:middle line:84%
We don't need
mutual independence.

00:03:57.868 --> 00:03:58.910 align:middle line:90%
What do we actually need?

00:03:58.910 --> 00:04:01.770 align:middle line:90%


00:04:01.770 --> 00:04:03.395 align:middle line:90%
Pairwise independence, yeah.

00:04:03.395 --> 00:04:10.823 align:middle line:90%


00:04:10.823 --> 00:04:12.990 align:middle line:84%
So if we have a bunch of
pairwise independent random

00:04:12.990 --> 00:04:15.640 align:middle line:84%
variables, we want to find
the variance of their sum.

00:04:15.640 --> 00:04:17.579 align:middle line:84%
We can instead just
sum the variances.

00:04:17.579 --> 00:04:21.899 align:middle line:90%
So another very useful fact--

00:04:21.899 --> 00:04:23.950 align:middle line:84%
hopefully, you proved it
already in recitation.

00:04:23.950 --> 00:04:25.533 align:middle line:84%
So we don't need to
go over the proof.

00:04:25.533 --> 00:04:27.780 align:middle line:90%


00:04:27.780 --> 00:04:31.997 align:middle line:84%
But these-- well,
these two formulas

00:04:31.997 --> 00:04:33.455 align:middle line:84%
are going to be
quite useful today.

00:04:33.455 --> 00:04:39.390 align:middle line:90%


00:04:39.390 --> 00:04:41.315 align:middle line:84%
Now, time for the first
of our tail bounds.

00:04:41.315 --> 00:04:51.300 align:middle line:90%


00:04:51.300 --> 00:04:56.920 align:middle line:84%
So before I give you the bound,
let's think about an example.

00:04:56.920 --> 00:05:01.590 align:middle line:84%
So looking at this room,
suppose I pick a random student.

00:05:01.590 --> 00:05:07.410 align:middle line:84%
And let the random
variable R be the row

00:05:07.410 --> 00:05:11.454 align:middle line:84%
that the randomly picked
student is sitting in.

00:05:11.454 --> 00:05:15.180 align:middle line:84%
So guesstimate that
this is about--

00:05:15.180 --> 00:05:17.050 align:middle line:90%
the expectation of R is about 8.

00:05:17.050 --> 00:05:20.450 align:middle line:90%
So pick random student.

00:05:20.450 --> 00:05:25.770 align:middle line:90%


00:05:25.770 --> 00:05:27.320 align:middle line:90%
R is the row.

00:05:27.320 --> 00:05:31.692 align:middle line:90%


00:05:31.692 --> 00:05:36.270 align:middle line:84%
So for those of you who aren't
in the room, those of you who

00:05:36.270 --> 00:05:38.850 align:middle line:84%
are watching the
video, what does that

00:05:38.850 --> 00:05:43.880 align:middle line:84%
tell them about the probability
that R is at least 16?

00:05:43.880 --> 00:05:56.880 align:middle line:90%


00:05:56.880 --> 00:05:59.580 align:middle line:84%
So what's the probability that
a randomly selected student is

00:05:59.580 --> 00:06:01.630 align:middle line:90%
sitting in the last five rows?

00:06:01.630 --> 00:06:03.370 align:middle line:90%
I think there are 21 rows here.

00:06:03.370 --> 00:06:03.870 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:06:03.870 --> 00:06:07.955 align:middle line:90%


00:06:07.955 --> 00:06:09.080 align:middle line:90%
Does anybody have any idea?

00:06:09.080 --> 00:06:13.258 align:middle line:90%


00:06:13.258 --> 00:06:15.050 align:middle line:84%
So maybe I should label
this as an example.

00:06:15.050 --> 00:06:18.330 align:middle line:90%


00:06:18.330 --> 00:06:19.920 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:06:19.920 --> 00:06:22.200 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: 1 minus
the CDF [INAUDIBLE].

00:06:22.200 --> 00:06:23.740 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN:
1 minus the CDF.

00:06:23.740 --> 00:06:27.180 align:middle line:84%
So the people
watching the video,

00:06:27.180 --> 00:06:28.560 align:middle line:84%
I assume they
can't see the room.

00:06:28.560 --> 00:06:31.510 align:middle line:84%
So they don't know
what the CDF is.

00:06:31.510 --> 00:06:35.870 align:middle line:84%
The only information they know
is that the expectation is 8.

00:06:35.870 --> 00:06:41.190 align:middle line:90%


00:06:41.190 --> 00:06:41.690 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:06:41.690 --> 00:06:43.482 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Can we find
the variance for that

00:06:43.482 --> 00:06:45.210 align:middle line:84%
and see how far away
you are from there?

00:06:45.210 --> 00:06:47.877 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Oh, can we find
the variance from that and then

00:06:47.877 --> 00:06:48.930 align:middle line:90%
see how far away we are?

00:06:48.930 --> 00:06:50.010 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:06:50.010 --> 00:06:54.010 align:middle line:84%
[LAUGHS] That requires
more information, right?

00:06:54.010 --> 00:06:58.590 align:middle line:84%
We need to know a little bit
more about what's going on.

00:06:58.590 --> 00:07:03.870 align:middle line:84%
We need to somehow figure out
the expectation of R minus 8

00:07:03.870 --> 00:07:05.130 align:middle line:90%
squared.

00:07:05.130 --> 00:07:07.020 align:middle line:84%
So, we need to know
something more about R

00:07:07.020 --> 00:07:09.630 align:middle line:90%
than just its expectation.

00:07:09.630 --> 00:07:10.350 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:07:10.350 --> 00:07:12.810 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Do you know
how many [INAUDIBLE]?

00:07:12.810 --> 00:07:15.550 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Yes,
there are 21, so 0 to 20.

00:07:15.550 --> 00:07:16.290 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Wait.

00:07:16.290 --> 00:07:19.990 align:middle line:84%
Can we assume that it's
uniformly distributed

00:07:19.990 --> 00:07:22.170 align:middle line:90%
and [INAUDIBLE].

00:07:22.170 --> 00:07:25.500 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Can we assume
that it's uniformly distributed?

00:07:25.500 --> 00:07:26.910 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:07:26.910 --> 00:07:28.860 align:middle line:90%
And in fact, it is not.

00:07:28.860 --> 00:07:31.710 align:middle line:84%
There seem to be more
students towards the front

00:07:31.710 --> 00:07:33.190 align:middle line:90%
than towards the back.

00:07:33.190 --> 00:07:33.840 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:07:33.840 --> 00:07:36.340 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
that there are 20 rows.

00:07:36.340 --> 00:07:38.650 align:middle line:84%
If you just think
there are 16 row,

00:07:38.650 --> 00:07:41.250 align:middle line:84%
we know that the way we
find the expected value

00:07:41.250 --> 00:07:45.240 align:middle line:84%
is multiplying each possible
outcome by its probability.

00:07:45.240 --> 00:07:49.140 align:middle line:84%
Since a is 60 multiplied by 1/2,
the probability is generally

00:07:49.140 --> 00:07:51.690 align:middle line:90%
[INAUDIBLE] to be less than 1/2.

00:07:51.690 --> 00:07:52.750 align:middle line:90%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Yeah.

00:07:52.750 --> 00:07:54.910 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: If you
factor in 16 or 20,

00:07:54.910 --> 00:07:59.310 align:middle line:84%
it gets to be more
fun math [INAUDIBLE].

00:07:59.310 --> 00:08:02.350 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Yeah, so your
intuition is great, though.

00:08:02.350 --> 00:08:10.650 align:middle line:84%
So, well, we're using the
observation that 16 is twice 8.

00:08:10.650 --> 00:08:15.120 align:middle line:84%
We're also using the observation
that the rows are numbered 0

00:08:15.120 --> 00:08:15.820 align:middle line:90%
through 20.

00:08:15.820 --> 00:08:18.450 align:middle line:90%
Like they're non-negative.

00:08:18.450 --> 00:08:27.210 align:middle line:84%
So what happens if more
than half of the students

00:08:27.210 --> 00:08:28.850 align:middle line:84%
are sitting in the
back five rows?

00:08:28.850 --> 00:08:33.750 align:middle line:90%


00:08:33.750 --> 00:08:35.980 align:middle line:84%
What does that tell us
about the expectation?

00:08:35.980 --> 00:08:42.630 align:middle line:90%


00:08:42.630 --> 00:08:45.630 align:middle line:84%
Well, if more than
half of the students

00:08:45.630 --> 00:08:51.810 align:middle line:84%
give us R is at least
16, that tells us

00:08:51.810 --> 00:08:56.040 align:middle line:84%
that the expectation
should be at least 8--

00:08:56.040 --> 00:09:00.210 align:middle line:84%
or sorry, more than 8, if
more than half of the students

00:09:00.210 --> 00:09:01.710 align:middle line:90%
are in the back.

00:09:01.710 --> 00:09:06.270 align:middle line:84%
So the converse of
that is that there

00:09:06.270 --> 00:09:10.650 align:middle line:84%
are at most, half of the
students in the back five rows.

00:09:10.650 --> 00:09:13.560 align:middle line:84%
So let's try and
formalize this intuition.

00:09:13.560 --> 00:09:16.390 align:middle line:84%
So this is what's known
as Markov's inequality.

00:09:16.390 --> 00:09:25.170 align:middle line:90%


00:09:25.170 --> 00:09:33.590 align:middle line:84%
So let R be a non-negative
random variable.

00:09:33.590 --> 00:09:36.390 align:middle line:90%


00:09:36.390 --> 00:09:40.890 align:middle line:84%
Then the probability
that R is greater than

00:09:40.890 --> 00:09:48.340 align:middle line:84%
or equal to x is less than or
equal to the expectation of R

00:09:48.340 --> 00:09:50.250 align:middle line:90%
divided by x.

00:09:50.250 --> 00:09:54.676 align:middle line:90%


00:09:54.676 --> 00:09:56.990 align:middle line:84%
So for the example
that we just saw,

00:09:56.990 --> 00:10:00.700 align:middle line:84%
the probability that
R is at least 16,

00:10:00.700 --> 00:10:05.570 align:middle line:84%
it's at most the expectation,
which is 8 divided by 16.

00:10:05.570 --> 00:10:06.460 align:middle line:90%
So that gives us 1/2.

00:10:06.460 --> 00:10:10.546 align:middle line:90%


00:10:10.546 --> 00:10:12.330 align:middle line:84%
Does the statement
make sense to people?

00:10:12.330 --> 00:10:25.390 align:middle line:90%


00:10:25.390 --> 00:10:27.363 align:middle line:84%
So basically, it's
saying that you

00:10:27.363 --> 00:10:29.530 align:middle line:84%
can't have too many super
large values, because that

00:10:29.530 --> 00:10:33.880 align:middle line:84%
would push the
expectation up too high

00:10:33.880 --> 00:10:36.015 align:middle line:90%
So how could we prove this?

00:10:36.015 --> 00:10:41.767 align:middle line:90%


00:10:41.767 --> 00:10:44.350 align:middle line:84%
And it is, how do we formalize
the intuition that we were just

00:10:44.350 --> 00:10:44.933 align:middle line:90%
talking about?

00:10:44.933 --> 00:10:57.680 align:middle line:90%


00:10:57.680 --> 00:11:00.250 align:middle line:84%
Let's try using the law
of total expectation.

00:11:00.250 --> 00:11:04.510 align:middle line:84%
So how can we write
the expectation of R?

00:11:04.510 --> 00:11:05.955 align:middle line:90%
What might we condition on?

00:11:05.955 --> 00:11:14.253 align:middle line:90%


00:11:14.253 --> 00:11:16.420 align:middle line:84%
We don't have too many
events that we can work with.

00:11:16.420 --> 00:11:20.785 align:middle line:90%


00:11:20.785 --> 00:11:22.035 align:middle line:90%
Which of them might be useful?

00:11:22.035 --> 00:11:32.230 align:middle line:90%


00:11:32.230 --> 00:11:32.950 align:middle line:90%
Nobody?

00:11:32.950 --> 00:11:41.040 align:middle line:84%
So let's try conditioning on
x greater than-- oh wait, x--

00:11:41.040 --> 00:11:44.020 align:middle line:90%


00:11:44.020 --> 00:11:45.810 align:middle line:84%
yeah, or greater
than or equal to x.

00:11:45.810 --> 00:11:48.994 align:middle line:90%


00:11:48.994 --> 00:11:52.270 align:middle line:84%
So what does the law of
total expectation tell us?

00:11:52.270 --> 00:11:57.760 align:middle line:84%
Well, this is going to be the
expectation of R conditioned

00:11:57.760 --> 00:12:03.550 align:middle line:84%
on R being greater than x
multiplied by the probability

00:12:03.550 --> 00:12:15.430 align:middle line:84%
that R is greater than x plus
the expectation R conditioned

00:12:15.430 --> 00:12:21.680 align:middle line:84%
on R less than x times
that probability.

00:12:21.680 --> 00:12:27.970 align:middle line:90%


00:12:27.970 --> 00:12:29.210 align:middle line:90%
Do people remember that?

00:12:29.210 --> 00:12:30.910 align:middle line:90%
Is that coming back?

00:12:30.910 --> 00:12:31.510 align:middle line:90%
Hopefully.

00:12:31.510 --> 00:12:32.010 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:12:32.010 --> 00:12:32.590 align:middle line:90%
No Maybe.

00:12:32.590 --> 00:12:33.255 align:middle line:90%
A few nods.

00:12:33.255 --> 00:12:36.550 align:middle line:90%


00:12:36.550 --> 00:12:40.420 align:middle line:84%
So what do we know about
each of these values?

00:12:40.420 --> 00:13:00.927 align:middle line:90%


00:13:00.927 --> 00:13:02.010 align:middle line:90%
Let's start with this one.

00:13:02.010 --> 00:13:03.295 align:middle line:90%
Can anybody bound this?

00:13:03.295 --> 00:13:14.330 align:middle line:90%


00:13:14.330 --> 00:13:15.170 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:13:15.170 --> 00:13:16.640 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: It's at least x.

00:13:16.640 --> 00:13:17.580 align:middle line:90%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Yeah.

00:13:17.580 --> 00:13:18.920 align:middle line:90%
It's at least x.

00:13:18.920 --> 00:13:23.270 align:middle line:84%
If you conditioned on R being
at least x, the expectation of R

00:13:23.270 --> 00:13:26.240 align:middle line:90%
is also going to be at least x.

00:13:26.240 --> 00:13:30.140 align:middle line:90%
Every outcome is at least x.

00:13:30.140 --> 00:13:35.750 align:middle line:84%
So this is going to
be at least x times--

00:13:35.750 --> 00:13:38.340 align:middle line:84%
well, this is the probability
that we're looking for.

00:13:38.340 --> 00:13:40.095 align:middle line:84%
So let's just write
it out as it is.

00:13:40.095 --> 00:13:49.412 align:middle line:90%


00:13:49.412 --> 00:13:50.790 align:middle line:90%
Now, what about the bottom line?

00:13:50.790 --> 00:13:53.920 align:middle line:90%


00:13:53.920 --> 00:13:56.000 align:middle line:84%
What do we know about
this expectation?

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:01.120 align:middle line:90%


00:14:01.120 --> 00:14:01.880 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:14:01.880 --> 00:14:05.500 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Is it 1 minus the
expectation of the other one?

00:14:05.500 --> 00:14:07.480 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Is it
1 minus the expectation

00:14:07.480 --> 00:14:09.100 align:middle line:90%
of the other one?

00:14:09.100 --> 00:14:09.620 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:14:09.620 --> 00:14:13.600 align:middle line:84%
So the probability is 1
minus the other probability.

00:14:13.600 --> 00:14:16.010 align:middle line:84%
The expectation does not
work like that, though.

00:14:16.010 --> 00:14:16.510 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:14:16.510 --> 00:14:17.605 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: At most, x.

00:14:17.605 --> 00:14:18.980 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN:
It is at most x.

00:14:18.980 --> 00:14:20.320 align:middle line:90%
That is true.

00:14:20.320 --> 00:14:24.755 align:middle line:84%
We're actually looking
for a lower bound, though.

00:14:24.755 --> 00:14:25.255 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:14:25.255 --> 00:14:27.755 align:middle line:90%


00:14:27.755 --> 00:14:28.630 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: At least 0.

00:14:28.630 --> 00:14:30.255 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: It's
at least 0, yeah.

00:14:30.255 --> 00:14:41.170 align:middle line:90%


00:14:41.170 --> 00:14:44.530 align:middle line:84%
We know that R is
always non-negative.

00:14:44.530 --> 00:14:49.060 align:middle line:84%
So conditioning on anything,
R is still always going

00:14:49.060 --> 00:14:50.530 align:middle line:90%
to be non-negative.

00:14:50.530 --> 00:14:52.970 align:middle line:84%
So its expectation has
to be non-negative.

00:14:52.970 --> 00:14:58.543 align:middle line:90%


00:14:58.543 --> 00:15:00.050 align:middle line:90%
So we can drop this.

00:15:00.050 --> 00:15:02.890 align:middle line:90%
This is just going to be 0.

00:15:02.890 --> 00:15:05.230 align:middle line:84%
Now we've got the
expectation of R

00:15:05.230 --> 00:15:12.160 align:middle line:84%
is at least x times
the probability

00:15:12.160 --> 00:15:13.135 align:middle line:90%
that R is at least x.

00:15:13.135 --> 00:15:21.940 align:middle line:90%


00:15:21.940 --> 00:15:38.110 align:middle line:84%
Now we can just move
this x to the other side,

00:15:38.110 --> 00:15:39.560 align:middle line:90%
assuming x is non-negative.

00:15:39.560 --> 00:15:44.260 align:middle line:84%
If x is negative, then it's a
very silly question-- or sorry,

00:15:44.260 --> 00:15:45.710 align:middle line:90%
assuming x is positive.

00:15:45.710 --> 00:15:48.560 align:middle line:90%


00:15:48.560 --> 00:15:49.935 align:middle line:84%
Are people happy
with this proof?

00:15:49.935 --> 00:15:52.870 align:middle line:90%


00:15:52.870 --> 00:15:54.590 align:middle line:90%
Does anybody have any questions?

00:15:54.590 --> 00:16:08.260 align:middle line:90%


00:16:08.260 --> 00:16:13.240 align:middle line:84%
So another form of Markov
which you may often encounter

00:16:13.240 --> 00:16:14.480 align:middle line:90%
is the following.

00:16:14.480 --> 00:16:25.690 align:middle line:90%


00:16:25.690 --> 00:16:35.630 align:middle line:84%
So the probability that R is at
least C times its expectation

00:16:35.630 --> 00:16:44.560 align:middle line:84%
is at most 1 over C
for any positive C--

00:16:44.560 --> 00:16:48.050 align:middle line:90%


00:16:48.050 --> 00:16:51.097 align:middle line:84%
so, essentially, equivalent
statement, just you

00:16:51.097 --> 00:16:52.930 align:middle line:84%
might sometimes see it
in this form instead.

00:16:52.930 --> 00:16:56.835 align:middle line:90%


00:16:56.835 --> 00:16:58.793 align:middle line:84%
So let's take a look at
a couple more examples.

00:16:58.793 --> 00:17:07.520 align:middle line:90%


00:17:07.520 --> 00:17:18.637 align:middle line:84%
So suppose R is the test score
of a randomly chosen student

00:17:18.637 --> 00:17:20.470 align:middle line:84%
instead of the roll
that they're sitting in.

00:17:20.470 --> 00:17:38.906 align:middle line:90%


00:17:38.906 --> 00:17:47.760 align:middle line:84%
And suppose that these are all
in the range, say, 30% to 100%.

00:17:47.760 --> 00:18:00.180 align:middle line:90%


00:18:00.180 --> 00:18:11.360 align:middle line:84%
Can we use Markov to bound the
probability that R is at least,

00:18:11.360 --> 00:18:12.223 align:middle line:90%
say, 90%?

00:18:12.223 --> 00:18:17.300 align:middle line:90%


00:18:17.300 --> 00:18:18.250 align:middle line:90%
How might we do that?

00:18:18.250 --> 00:18:29.150 align:middle line:90%


00:18:29.150 --> 00:18:31.622 align:middle line:84%
Sorry, I completely forgot
to give you the expectation.

00:18:31.622 --> 00:18:32.330 align:middle line:90%
The answer is no.

00:18:32.330 --> 00:18:41.100 align:middle line:90%


00:18:41.100 --> 00:18:42.426 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:18:42.426 --> 00:18:44.703 align:middle line:90%
Now can you do it?

00:18:44.703 --> 00:18:46.370 align:middle line:84%
Hopefully, it's a
little bit easier now.

00:18:46.370 --> 00:18:58.260 align:middle line:90%


00:18:58.260 --> 00:18:59.454 align:middle line:90%
Mm-hmm?

00:18:59.454 --> 00:19:06.703 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: What if [INAUDIBLE]
value of C such that C times 75

00:19:06.703 --> 00:19:07.363 align:middle line:90%
is 90.

00:19:07.363 --> 00:19:08.280 align:middle line:90%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Yeah.

00:19:08.280 --> 00:19:14.040 align:middle line:84%
So find the value of C
such that C times 75 is 90.

00:19:14.040 --> 00:19:17.740 align:middle line:90%
So I guess 75--

00:19:17.740 --> 00:19:26.722 align:middle line:84%
or 90 divided by 75,
that's, what's, 1.2.

00:19:26.722 --> 00:19:27.305 align:middle line:90%
Is that right?

00:19:27.305 --> 00:19:30.410 align:middle line:90%


00:19:30.410 --> 00:19:34.070 align:middle line:90%
75 is 5 by 15, 96 by 15.

00:19:34.070 --> 00:19:38.406 align:middle line:90%
OK, nice, arithmetic, score.

00:19:38.406 --> 00:19:44.450 align:middle line:84%
So then using this
formulation here,

00:19:44.450 --> 00:19:49.850 align:middle line:84%
we have the
probability that R is

00:19:49.850 --> 00:20:02.180 align:middle line:84%
at least 1.2 times
expectation of R is at most 1

00:20:02.180 --> 00:20:05.130 align:middle line:90%
divided by 1.2.

00:20:05.130 --> 00:20:07.673 align:middle line:84%
So this is going to
be something like 83%.

00:20:07.673 --> 00:20:17.190 align:middle line:90%


00:20:17.190 --> 00:20:19.970 align:middle line:84%
People reasonably
happy with that?

00:20:19.970 --> 00:20:20.810 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:20:20.810 --> 00:20:23.965 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Can you please expand
a little bit [INAUDIBLE]?

00:20:23.965 --> 00:20:25.340 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN:
Oh, the question

00:20:25.340 --> 00:20:28.310 align:middle line:84%
is, can we explain the
difference between these two

00:20:28.310 --> 00:20:29.580 align:middle line:90%
formulations?

00:20:29.580 --> 00:20:30.757 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:20:30.757 --> 00:20:31.715 align:middle line:90%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Sorry?

00:20:31.715 --> 00:20:33.827 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:20:33.827 --> 00:20:35.660 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: So
yeah, essentially, there

00:20:35.660 --> 00:20:36.710 align:middle line:90%
is no difference.

00:20:36.710 --> 00:20:40.980 align:middle line:84%
They're just different ways
of thinking about the bound.

00:20:40.980 --> 00:20:43.010 align:middle line:84%
You can either think
about bounding it in terms

00:20:43.010 --> 00:20:45.150 align:middle line:90%
of some absolute threshold.

00:20:45.150 --> 00:20:47.360 align:middle line:84%
Or you can think
about it as in terms

00:20:47.360 --> 00:20:51.860 align:middle line:84%
of some relative threshold,
multiply the expectation

00:20:51.860 --> 00:20:55.224 align:middle line:90%
by some scaling factor.

00:20:55.224 --> 00:20:58.760 align:middle line:84%
So, depending on which of them
feels more natural to you,

00:20:58.760 --> 00:21:01.160 align:middle line:84%
we could also use the
first formulation to say,

00:21:01.160 --> 00:21:06.995 align:middle line:84%
probability that R is greater
than 90 greater than or equal to

00:21:06.995 --> 00:21:16.730 align:middle line:84%
is going to be at most, 75
over 90, which same thing, 83%.

00:21:16.730 --> 00:21:18.298 align:middle line:90%
So either of them works.

00:21:18.298 --> 00:21:19.590 align:middle line:90%
They both give the same answer.

00:21:19.590 --> 00:21:20.923 align:middle line:90%
They're equivalent formulations.

00:21:20.923 --> 00:21:23.630 align:middle line:84%
It's just whichever one you
find easier to think about.

00:21:23.630 --> 00:21:25.010 align:middle line:90%
Question?

00:21:25.010 --> 00:21:28.200 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Based on the fact that
we know the range is 30 to 100,

00:21:28.200 --> 00:21:34.120 align:middle line:84%
not 0 to 100, is there a way to
make the final probability more

00:21:34.120 --> 00:21:34.620 align:middle line:90%
accurate?

00:21:34.620 --> 00:21:36.330 align:middle line:90%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Yes, exactly.

00:21:36.330 --> 00:21:39.350 align:middle line:84%
So the question
was, we don't just

00:21:39.350 --> 00:21:41.560 align:middle line:84%
have a non-negative
random variable R. Right.

00:21:41.560 --> 00:21:43.310 align:middle line:84%
We've actually got an
even stronger bound.

00:21:43.310 --> 00:21:46.040 align:middle line:84%
R is at least 30,
not just at least 0.

00:21:46.040 --> 00:21:50.020 align:middle line:84%
So can we leverage that to
get an even stronger bound?

00:21:50.020 --> 00:21:52.760 align:middle line:90%


00:21:52.760 --> 00:21:54.055 align:middle line:90%
So how could we do that?

00:21:54.055 --> 00:21:57.337 align:middle line:90%


00:21:57.337 --> 00:21:59.545 align:middle line:84%
Well, let's try defining a
different random variable.

00:21:59.545 --> 00:22:06.530 align:middle line:90%


00:22:06.530 --> 00:22:13.525 align:middle line:90%
So let R prime be R negative 30.

00:22:13.525 --> 00:22:20.410 align:middle line:90%


00:22:20.410 --> 00:22:22.063 align:middle line:84%
So this is another
random variable.

00:22:22.063 --> 00:22:23.730 align:middle line:84%
We're just going to
take our original R.

00:22:23.730 --> 00:22:26.107 align:middle line:90%
We're going to subtract 30.

00:22:26.107 --> 00:22:28.690 align:middle line:84%
We're not going to do this to
people's exam scores in reality.

00:22:28.690 --> 00:22:30.600 align:middle line:90%
Don't worry.

00:22:30.600 --> 00:22:33.060 align:middle line:84%
But that this makes the
minimum exam score 0.

00:22:33.060 --> 00:22:35.835 align:middle line:90%


00:22:35.835 --> 00:22:40.110 align:middle line:84%
So the hope is that now we're
satisfying the condition

00:22:40.110 --> 00:22:44.530 align:middle line:84%
to Markov's inequality
more tightly.

00:22:44.530 --> 00:22:48.370 align:middle line:84%
So hopefully, Markov will
give us a tighter bound.

00:22:48.370 --> 00:22:50.070 align:middle line:84%
So what bound does
it give us now?

00:22:50.070 --> 00:22:54.875 align:middle line:84%
What is the probability
that R is at least 90?

00:22:54.875 --> 00:23:00.360 align:middle line:90%


00:23:00.360 --> 00:23:03.068 align:middle line:84%
Well, what is that
in terms of R prime.

00:23:03.068 --> 00:23:03.860 align:middle line:90%
What is that event?

00:23:03.860 --> 00:23:09.660 align:middle line:90%


00:23:09.660 --> 00:23:10.380 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:23:10.380 --> 00:23:12.030 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:23:12.030 --> 00:23:13.380 align:middle line:90%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Yeah.

00:23:13.380 --> 00:23:17.100 align:middle line:84%
So this is the same event,
and so the same probability

00:23:17.100 --> 00:23:19.393 align:middle line:90%
that r prime is at least 60.

00:23:19.393 --> 00:23:28.152 align:middle line:90%


00:23:28.152 --> 00:23:30.110 align:middle line:84%
Now, what happens when
we apply Markov to this?

00:23:30.110 --> 00:23:44.880 align:middle line:90%


00:23:44.880 --> 00:23:58.050 align:middle line:84%
Well, this is going to be at
most, the expectation of R

00:23:58.050 --> 00:24:03.000 align:middle line:90%
prime divided by 60.

00:24:03.000 --> 00:24:04.730 align:middle line:84%
What is the
expectation of R prime?

00:24:04.730 --> 00:24:17.070 align:middle line:90%


00:24:17.070 --> 00:24:18.040 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:24:18.040 --> 00:24:18.720 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: 45.

00:24:18.720 --> 00:24:22.320 align:middle line:90%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: 45, yeah.

00:24:22.320 --> 00:24:24.720 align:middle line:84%
So this is going to
be the expectation

00:24:24.720 --> 00:24:34.120 align:middle line:84%
of R minus 30 divided by 60,
which is the expectation.

00:24:34.120 --> 00:24:36.750 align:middle line:84%
So linearity of expectation,
we can pull this--

00:24:36.750 --> 00:24:40.270 align:middle line:84%
or we can split this
into two expectations.

00:24:40.270 --> 00:24:46.110 align:middle line:84%
So this is the expectation of
R minus the expectation of 30.

00:24:46.110 --> 00:24:48.400 align:middle line:84%
There's not really any
randomness involved there.

00:24:48.400 --> 00:24:52.990 align:middle line:90%
It's just 30 over 60.

00:24:52.990 --> 00:24:56.760 align:middle line:90%
So this is 45 over 60.

00:24:56.760 --> 00:24:59.340 align:middle line:90%


00:24:59.340 --> 00:25:00.970 align:middle line:84%
Does that make
sense to everybody?

00:25:00.970 --> 00:25:04.080 align:middle line:90%


00:25:04.080 --> 00:25:08.828 align:middle line:84%
So now, instead of this
bound of it's at most 83%,

00:25:08.828 --> 00:25:10.120 align:middle line:90%
now we've got the better bound.

00:25:10.120 --> 00:25:10.828 align:middle line:90%
It's at most 75%.

00:25:10.828 --> 00:25:19.015 align:middle line:90%


00:25:19.015 --> 00:25:21.473 align:middle line:84%
So by shifting our
random variable,

00:25:21.473 --> 00:25:23.015 align:middle line:84%
we've managed to
get a tighter bound.

00:25:23.015 --> 00:25:33.960 align:middle line:90%


00:25:33.960 --> 00:25:48.090 align:middle line:84%
What about the probability
that R is at most 65?

00:25:48.090 --> 00:25:49.140 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:25:49.140 --> 00:25:54.078 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: For the previous
one, where R is from 30 to 100,

00:25:54.078 --> 00:25:58.290 align:middle line:84%
is that only the
[INAUDIBLE] assumed

00:25:58.290 --> 00:26:03.480 align:middle line:84%
that the lower bound for
x is 0, and that somehow,

00:26:03.480 --> 00:26:05.320 align:middle line:90%
the lower bound for R is 30.

00:26:05.320 --> 00:26:10.563 align:middle line:84%
So I [INAUDIBLE] do a
more complicated thing.

00:26:10.563 --> 00:26:12.730 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: So that's
kind of what we're doing.

00:26:12.730 --> 00:26:15.400 align:middle line:84%
The question was, in
the proof of Markov,

00:26:15.400 --> 00:26:18.360 align:middle line:84%
we're assuming that
the lower bound is 0.

00:26:18.360 --> 00:26:20.440 align:middle line:84%
Here we've got a lower
bound of 30 instead.

00:26:20.440 --> 00:26:22.630 align:middle line:84%
So do we need to do
something more complicated?

00:26:22.630 --> 00:26:24.670 align:middle line:84%
The answer is no,
we don't have to.

00:26:24.670 --> 00:26:27.340 align:middle line:84%
But if we do, it gives
us a stronger result.

00:26:27.340 --> 00:26:29.160 align:middle line:90%
So that's what we've done here.

00:26:29.160 --> 00:26:31.030 align:middle line:90%
But we don't have to do it.

00:26:31.030 --> 00:26:35.220 align:middle line:84%
Because 0 is still
a valid lower bound.

00:26:35.220 --> 00:26:37.770 align:middle line:84%
We could say that
the co-domain of R

00:26:37.770 --> 00:26:40.020 align:middle line:84%
is 0 to 100 instead
of 30 to 100,

00:26:40.020 --> 00:26:43.960 align:middle line:84%
even if the range
stays unchanged.

00:26:43.960 --> 00:26:46.240 align:middle line:84%
So it's still a non-negative
random variable.

00:26:46.240 --> 00:26:48.400 align:middle line:84%
So we're still allowed
to apply Markov to it.

00:26:48.400 --> 00:26:51.600 align:middle line:84%
It's just that doing it
on R instead of R prime

00:26:51.600 --> 00:26:56.910 align:middle line:84%
gives us a weaker result. Does
that make sense to everybody?

00:26:56.910 --> 00:26:58.150 align:middle line:90%
Another question?

00:26:58.150 --> 00:27:00.240 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
you mean use a tighter

00:27:00.240 --> 00:27:02.880 align:middle line:90%
bound when you shift on.

00:27:02.880 --> 00:27:05.160 align:middle line:84%
Does a tighter bound
mean that the probability

00:27:05.160 --> 00:27:06.370 align:middle line:90%
is lower or higher?

00:27:06.370 --> 00:27:07.870 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN:
So the question is,

00:27:07.870 --> 00:27:11.460 align:middle line:84%
what do I mean by a tighter
bound when we shift R?

00:27:11.460 --> 00:27:16.660 align:middle line:84%
So tighter in the sense
that it is stronger.

00:27:16.660 --> 00:27:22.360 align:middle line:84%
So R at least 30 implies
that R is at least 0.

00:27:22.360 --> 00:27:29.530 align:middle line:84%
So R at least 30 is a stronger
condition than R at least 0.

00:27:29.530 --> 00:27:31.980 align:middle line:84%
So that's what I
mean by tighter.

00:27:31.980 --> 00:27:33.780 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So what's
the difference

00:27:33.780 --> 00:27:38.010 align:middle line:84%
between the 75% that
we got here for R

00:27:38.010 --> 00:27:41.430 align:middle line:84%
is greater than or equal
to 90 versus the 83%?

00:27:41.430 --> 00:27:44.460 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN:
So the difference

00:27:44.460 --> 00:27:47.970 align:middle line:90%
is how we're applying Markov.

00:27:47.970 --> 00:27:51.240 align:middle line:84%
In the first case, we're
applying Markov to R directly.

00:27:51.240 --> 00:27:55.230 align:middle line:84%
In the second case, we are
creating a new random variable.

00:27:55.230 --> 00:27:57.100 align:middle line:84%
And we're applying
Markov to that.

00:27:57.100 --> 00:28:05.693 align:middle line:84%
And because we've got a
stronger condition, Markov's--

00:28:05.693 --> 00:28:07.110 align:middle line:84%
what do you call
it-- precondition

00:28:07.110 --> 00:28:15.785 align:middle line:84%
is tight now, we can get
a stronger result. Yeah?

00:28:15.785 --> 00:28:18.120 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: I also
have a question.

00:28:18.120 --> 00:28:20.790 align:middle line:84%
So does that mean it's
depending on the situation

00:28:20.790 --> 00:28:26.370 align:middle line:84%
to [INAUDIBLE] it could
go higher than 83%?

00:28:26.370 --> 00:28:28.346 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Could
it go higher than 83%?

00:28:28.346 --> 00:28:31.203 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:28:31.203 --> 00:28:33.370 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: So we will
get to that in a moment.

00:28:33.370 --> 00:28:37.020 align:middle line:84%
The question is, if we're
in a different situation,

00:28:37.020 --> 00:28:38.670 align:middle line:84%
could shifting it
give us something

00:28:38.670 --> 00:28:40.510 align:middle line:90%
that's higher than 83%?

00:28:40.510 --> 00:28:44.400 align:middle line:90%
And the answer is yes-ish.

00:28:44.400 --> 00:28:47.730 align:middle line:84%
In the case where we've
applied Markov incorrectly

00:28:47.730 --> 00:28:50.670 align:middle line:90%
the first time, then yes.

00:28:50.670 --> 00:28:55.080 align:middle line:84%
But if we've applied
Markov correctly,

00:28:55.080 --> 00:28:59.610 align:middle line:90%
then the first is a valid bound.

00:28:59.610 --> 00:29:03.460 align:middle line:84%
So we could, in
principle, improve it.

00:29:03.460 --> 00:29:06.540 align:middle line:84%
But we're not going
to do any worse

00:29:06.540 --> 00:29:09.810 align:middle line:90%
by imposing tighter conditions.

00:29:09.810 --> 00:29:13.063 align:middle line:84%
Does that at least kind
of intuitively make sense?

00:29:13.063 --> 00:29:15.105 align:middle line:84%
I'll give you a more
complete answer in a moment.

00:29:15.105 --> 00:29:18.545 align:middle line:90%


00:29:18.545 --> 00:29:20.170 align:middle line:84%
Any more questions
about this before we

00:29:20.170 --> 00:29:22.730 align:middle line:90%
move on to the next example?

00:29:22.730 --> 00:29:23.230 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:29:23.230 --> 00:29:25.480 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So it's a
good thing that the 75%

00:29:25.480 --> 00:29:27.590 align:middle line:90%
is lower than the 83%?

00:29:27.590 --> 00:29:29.840 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Yes,
it is a good thing.

00:29:29.840 --> 00:29:32.950 align:middle line:84%
So the question is, is it
a good thing that the 75%

00:29:32.950 --> 00:29:35.020 align:middle line:90%
is smaller than the 83%?

00:29:35.020 --> 00:29:35.710 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:29:35.710 --> 00:29:38.810 align:middle line:84%
We are looking for an upper
bound on the probability.

00:29:38.810 --> 00:29:42.020 align:middle line:84%
So a smaller upper bound
is a stronger condition.

00:29:42.020 --> 00:29:43.310 align:middle line:90%
So that's better.

00:29:43.310 --> 00:29:46.145 align:middle line:90%
It's a stronger bound.

00:29:46.145 --> 00:29:47.770 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: We want a
smaller upper bound

00:29:47.770 --> 00:29:48.853 align:middle line:90%
or a stronger [INAUDIBLE]?

00:29:48.853 --> 00:29:50.395 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: So
they're the same.

00:29:50.395 --> 00:29:52.360 align:middle line:84%
Smaller upper bounds are
stronger upper bounds.

00:29:52.360 --> 00:29:52.860 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:29:52.860 --> 00:29:56.650 align:middle line:90%


00:29:56.650 --> 00:30:00.747 align:middle line:84%
So less than or equal to 83%
implies less than or equal to--

00:30:00.747 --> 00:30:02.830 align:middle line:84%
sorry, less than or equal
to 75% implies less than

00:30:02.830 --> 00:30:04.550 align:middle line:90%
or equal to 83%.

00:30:04.550 --> 00:30:06.285 align:middle line:90%
So 75 is stronger.

00:30:06.285 --> 00:30:13.613 align:middle line:90%


00:30:13.613 --> 00:30:16.030 align:middle line:84%
Have people had enough time
to think about the probability

00:30:16.030 --> 00:30:17.143 align:middle line:90%
that R is at most 65?

00:30:17.143 --> 00:30:21.490 align:middle line:90%


00:30:21.490 --> 00:30:23.775 align:middle line:84%
How might we use Markov
to figure this one out?

00:30:23.775 --> 00:30:28.570 align:middle line:90%


00:30:28.570 --> 00:30:29.290 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:30:29.290 --> 00:30:31.480 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Can you do
1 minus probability

00:30:31.480 --> 00:30:35.930 align:middle line:90%
that R is greater than 65.

00:30:35.930 --> 00:30:37.930 align:middle line:90%
So [INAUDIBLE].

00:30:37.930 --> 00:30:41.238 align:middle line:90%


00:30:41.238 --> 00:30:45.500 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: So R
greater than or equal to 66,

00:30:45.500 --> 00:30:48.970 align:middle line:90%
so if we assume integer scores.

00:30:48.970 --> 00:30:49.470 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:30:49.470 --> 00:30:52.470 align:middle line:90%


00:30:52.470 --> 00:30:55.245 align:middle line:84%
And what does Markov
tell us about this?

00:30:55.245 --> 00:31:16.960 align:middle line:90%


00:31:16.960 --> 00:31:23.380 align:middle line:84%
Well, the probability
that R is at least 66

00:31:23.380 --> 00:31:32.200 align:middle line:84%
is going to be at most 75 over
66, which is bigger than 1.

00:31:32.200 --> 00:31:35.422 align:middle line:84%
So applying Markov does not
tell us anything useful.

00:31:35.422 --> 00:31:37.630 align:middle line:84%
It tells us that this is a
probability that's bounded

00:31:37.630 --> 00:31:39.420 align:middle line:90%
by 1, which we already knew.

00:31:39.420 --> 00:31:43.870 align:middle line:90%


00:31:43.870 --> 00:31:45.965 align:middle line:90%
So it is a good idea.

00:31:45.965 --> 00:31:47.340 align:middle line:84%
It's not quite
what we want here.

00:31:47.340 --> 00:31:59.830 align:middle line:90%


00:31:59.830 --> 00:32:03.880 align:middle line:84%
So what if instead of
fiddling with the event,

00:32:03.880 --> 00:32:08.085 align:middle line:84%
we fiddle with R again, kind of
similar to what we did before?

00:32:08.085 --> 00:32:16.480 align:middle line:90%


00:32:16.480 --> 00:32:17.200 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:32:17.200 --> 00:32:19.900 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
that R [INAUDIBLE].

00:32:19.900 --> 00:32:22.450 align:middle line:90%


00:32:22.450 --> 00:32:23.780 align:middle line:90%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Yeah, exactly.

00:32:23.780 --> 00:32:27.220 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to
flip R. So we're

00:32:27.220 --> 00:32:29.000 align:middle line:84%
going to define a
new random variable.

00:32:29.000 --> 00:32:40.510 align:middle line:84%
Let's say S equals 100 minus R.
So now the probability that R

00:32:40.510 --> 00:32:46.000 align:middle line:84%
is at most 65 is the
probability that S is at least,

00:32:46.000 --> 00:32:48.385 align:middle line:90%
what, 100 minus 65?

00:32:48.385 --> 00:32:48.885 align:middle line:90%
35.

00:32:48.885 --> 00:32:52.690 align:middle line:90%


00:32:52.690 --> 00:32:54.910 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:32:54.910 --> 00:32:56.400 align:middle line:90%
Can we apply Markov to that?

00:32:56.400 --> 00:32:59.685 align:middle line:90%


00:32:59.685 --> 00:33:00.560 align:middle line:90%
I'm seeing some nods.

00:33:00.560 --> 00:33:02.143 align:middle line:84%
Does anybody want
to do that and spare

00:33:02.143 --> 00:33:03.636 align:middle line:84%
me the trouble of
doing arithmetic?

00:33:03.636 --> 00:33:06.550 align:middle line:90%


00:33:06.550 --> 00:33:07.360 align:middle line:90%
Nobody?

00:33:07.360 --> 00:33:07.860 align:middle line:90%
Sadness.

00:33:07.860 --> 00:33:11.170 align:middle line:90%


00:33:11.170 --> 00:33:13.790 align:middle line:90%
Well, what does Markov say?

00:33:13.790 --> 00:33:17.980 align:middle line:84%
Well, it's at most
the expectation of x--

00:33:17.980 --> 00:33:21.375 align:middle line:90%
oh, sorry S-- divided by 35.

00:33:21.375 --> 00:33:24.010 align:middle line:90%


00:33:24.010 --> 00:33:27.730 align:middle line:90%
What is the expectation of S?

00:33:27.730 --> 00:33:29.890 align:middle line:84%
Well, using linearity
in the same way

00:33:29.890 --> 00:33:32.560 align:middle line:84%
that we did a
moment ago, this is

00:33:32.560 --> 00:33:38.150 align:middle line:84%
going to be equal to, what,
100 minus the expectation of R,

00:33:38.150 --> 00:33:42.050 align:middle line:90%
which is 75, over 35.

00:33:42.050 --> 00:33:44.030 align:middle line:90%
So that's 25 over 35.

00:33:44.030 --> 00:33:44.733 align:middle line:90%
This is 5/7.

00:33:44.733 --> 00:33:54.845 align:middle line:90%


00:33:54.845 --> 00:33:57.310 align:middle line:84%
So does that make
sense to everybody?

00:33:57.310 --> 00:34:01.223 align:middle line:84%
There is at most, a 5/7 chance
that you did worse than 65.

00:34:01.223 --> 00:34:25.452 align:middle line:90%


00:34:25.452 --> 00:34:28.179 align:middle line:84%
Now, perhaps not terribly
realistic in terms of exam

00:34:28.179 --> 00:34:32.500 align:middle line:84%
scores, but what if,
say, some of the students

00:34:32.500 --> 00:34:36.400 align:middle line:84%
did so badly that they got
scores that are less than 0?

00:34:36.400 --> 00:34:53.464 align:middle line:84%
Maybe you've got R is in
the range minus 30 to 100.

00:34:53.464 --> 00:34:59.303 align:middle line:84%
Same deal, expectation
of R Is 75.

00:34:59.303 --> 00:35:06.002 align:middle line:90%


00:35:06.002 --> 00:35:11.100 align:middle line:90%
A question, or-- sorry.

00:35:11.100 --> 00:35:13.850 align:middle line:84%
So what can we say
about the probability

00:35:13.850 --> 00:35:18.520 align:middle line:90%
that R is at least, say, 90?

00:35:18.520 --> 00:35:27.272 align:middle line:90%


00:35:27.272 --> 00:35:28.264 align:middle line:90%
Mm-hmm?

00:35:28.264 --> 00:35:30.248 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: So Markov [INAUDIBLE]?

00:35:30.248 --> 00:35:33.470 align:middle line:90%


00:35:33.470 --> 00:35:34.980 align:middle line:90%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Yeah, exactly.

00:35:34.980 --> 00:35:39.750 align:middle line:84%
So the observation was if we
try to apply Markov to this--

00:35:39.750 --> 00:35:42.420 align:middle line:84%
maybe I should call it
something different.

00:35:42.420 --> 00:35:53.715 align:middle line:84%
Let's call it T. So if we
try to apply Markov to T,

00:35:53.715 --> 00:35:56.090 align:middle line:84%
it's going to be the same
thing as when we applied Markov

00:35:56.090 --> 00:35:57.000 align:middle line:90%
to R before.

00:35:57.000 --> 00:35:58.920 align:middle line:90%
It will give us a bound of 83%.

00:35:58.920 --> 00:36:01.160 align:middle line:84%
The problem is
that that's wrong.

00:36:01.160 --> 00:36:04.500 align:middle line:84%
T does not satisfy the
precondition for Markov.

00:36:04.500 --> 00:36:10.785 align:middle line:84%
So what we want to do instead is
define T prime equals T plus 30.

00:36:10.785 --> 00:36:14.850 align:middle line:90%


00:36:14.850 --> 00:36:18.540 align:middle line:84%
And now if we apply Markov
to T prime, what do we get?

00:36:18.540 --> 00:36:25.260 align:middle line:84%
So the probability that
T is greater than 90

00:36:25.260 --> 00:36:34.440 align:middle line:84%
is the probability that
T prime is at least 120.

00:36:34.440 --> 00:36:39.570 align:middle line:84%
And by Markov, this is
going to be expectation

00:36:39.570 --> 00:36:45.810 align:middle line:90%
of T prime over 120.

00:36:45.810 --> 00:36:48.510 align:middle line:84%
And same deal as
before, linearity here

00:36:48.510 --> 00:36:55.878 align:middle line:90%
gives us 75 plus 30 over 120.

00:36:55.878 --> 00:37:01.410 align:middle line:90%
105 over 120, that's 7/8.

00:37:01.410 --> 00:37:03.585 align:middle line:90%
Is that right?

00:37:03.585 --> 00:37:04.085 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:37:04.085 --> 00:37:11.030 align:middle line:90%


00:37:11.030 --> 00:37:14.392 align:middle line:84%
So in this case, we
do get, in some sense,

00:37:14.392 --> 00:37:16.850 align:middle line:84%
a weaker bound than we would
have gotten by applying Markov

00:37:16.850 --> 00:37:19.130 align:middle line:90%
to T directly.

00:37:19.130 --> 00:37:22.650 align:middle line:84%
But applying Markov to T
directly doesn't actually work.

00:37:22.650 --> 00:37:25.350 align:middle line:84%
This looks weaker, but
it's a correct bound.

00:37:25.350 --> 00:37:28.910 align:middle line:84%
So hopefully, that answers
your question more fully.

00:37:28.910 --> 00:37:34.160 align:middle line:90%
Does anybody have any questions?

00:37:34.160 --> 00:37:37.040 align:middle line:84%
So even though we couldn't
apply Markov directly to T,

00:37:37.040 --> 00:37:39.470 align:middle line:84%
we can create a new
random variable T prime,

00:37:39.470 --> 00:37:42.320 align:middle line:90%
to which Markov does apply.

00:37:42.320 --> 00:37:43.295 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:37:43.295 --> 00:37:45.600 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Got a
question before about 30

00:37:45.600 --> 00:37:49.220 align:middle line:84%
being a lower bound to make
our statement any stronger

00:37:49.220 --> 00:37:51.210 align:middle line:90%
for S [INAUDIBLE].

00:37:51.210 --> 00:37:55.220 align:middle line:90%


00:37:55.220 --> 00:37:57.470 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: So using
the lower bound of 30 making

00:37:57.470 --> 00:38:01.448 align:middle line:90%
the statement stronger for T?

00:38:01.448 --> 00:38:02.396 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: For S.

00:38:02.396 --> 00:38:08.810 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Oh, for S.
Which one was S. Ah, S here?

00:38:08.810 --> 00:38:15.050 align:middle line:84%
So that does not really
help us in this case.

00:38:15.050 --> 00:38:22.580 align:middle line:84%
Because that corresponds to
an upper bound rather than

00:38:22.580 --> 00:38:24.200 align:middle line:90%
a lower bound.

00:38:24.200 --> 00:38:28.410 align:middle line:84%
And upper bounds don't really
appear in the proof of Markov.

00:38:28.410 --> 00:38:30.420 align:middle line:84%
We're not really
using them in any way.

00:38:30.420 --> 00:38:36.620 align:middle line:84%
So imposing a stronger upper
bound doesn't really help.

00:38:36.620 --> 00:38:39.950 align:middle line:90%
Does that answer your question?

00:38:39.950 --> 00:38:42.800 align:middle line:90%
OK, cool.

00:38:42.800 --> 00:38:43.610 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:38:43.610 --> 00:38:46.550 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Is that always the
case that the lowest lower bound

00:38:46.550 --> 00:38:51.147 align:middle line:84%
appears [INAUDIBLE] lowest
value here includes 0?

00:38:51.147 --> 00:38:52.730 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Is
it always the case

00:38:52.730 --> 00:38:54.690 align:middle line:84%
that the best lower
bound appears-- or sorry,

00:38:54.690 --> 00:39:01.010 align:middle line:84%
the best upper bound, I guess,
appears when the range actually

00:39:01.010 --> 00:39:01.765 align:middle line:90%
includes 0?

00:39:01.765 --> 00:39:04.280 align:middle line:90%


00:39:04.280 --> 00:39:14.020 align:middle line:84%
Essentially, yes, as far as
correct bounds go, anyway.

00:39:14.020 --> 00:39:20.310 align:middle line:90%


00:39:20.310 --> 00:39:26.310 align:middle line:84%
So I guess there's a
question of morally,

00:39:26.310 --> 00:39:30.410 align:middle line:84%
why do we need this
non-negativity?

00:39:30.410 --> 00:39:36.230 align:middle line:84%
And perhaps a very simple
illustrative example

00:39:36.230 --> 00:39:39.320 align:middle line:84%
is, suppose we have the
random variable R, which

00:39:39.320 --> 00:39:45.090 align:middle line:84%
is plus or minus 1, depending
on a fair coin flip.

00:39:45.090 --> 00:39:52.100 align:middle line:84%
So it's uniform on
positive 1 and negative 1.

00:39:52.100 --> 00:39:54.710 align:middle line:90%


00:39:54.710 --> 00:40:00.510 align:middle line:84%
So if we try to apply
Markov to that directly,

00:40:00.510 --> 00:40:05.130 align:middle line:84%
what does that tell us about the
probability that R is greater

00:40:05.130 --> 00:40:06.160 align:middle line:90%
than 1/2?

00:40:06.160 --> 00:40:27.270 align:middle line:90%


00:40:27.270 --> 00:40:30.960 align:middle line:84%
Well, if we try to apply Markov
directly, the expectation of R

00:40:30.960 --> 00:40:31.520 align:middle line:90%
is 0.

00:40:31.520 --> 00:40:34.110 align:middle line:90%


00:40:34.110 --> 00:40:38.250 align:middle line:84%
So no matter what
we put here, Markov

00:40:38.250 --> 00:40:45.180 align:middle line:84%
would try to tell us that the
probability is at most, 0.

00:40:45.180 --> 00:40:48.190 align:middle line:90%
That is clearly rubbish.

00:40:48.190 --> 00:40:50.640 align:middle line:84%
Because R can be
greater than 1/2.

00:40:50.640 --> 00:40:52.770 align:middle line:84%
R takes value 1 with
probability 1/2.

00:40:52.770 --> 00:40:56.368 align:middle line:90%


00:40:56.368 --> 00:40:59.060 align:middle line:90%
So basically, in our proof--

00:40:59.060 --> 00:41:00.455 align:middle line:90%
where was it?

00:41:00.455 --> 00:41:00.955 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:41:00.955 --> 00:41:04.550 align:middle line:90%


00:41:04.550 --> 00:41:08.160 align:middle line:84%
So if we get rid of the
non-negativity constraint,

00:41:08.160 --> 00:41:11.580 align:middle line:90%
then this no longer works.

00:41:11.580 --> 00:41:17.330 align:middle line:84%
We can't discard this
term, because that 0,

00:41:17.330 --> 00:41:20.310 align:middle line:84%
if we don't know that the
random variable is non-negative,

00:41:20.310 --> 00:41:23.670 align:middle line:84%
we could, in principle,
have a negative value there,

00:41:23.670 --> 00:41:26.335 align:middle line:90%
which we can't get rid of.

00:41:26.335 --> 00:41:35.090 align:middle line:90%


00:41:35.090 --> 00:41:39.175 align:middle line:84%
So another question,
is Markov tight?

00:41:39.175 --> 00:41:57.030 align:middle line:90%


00:41:57.030 --> 00:42:02.070 align:middle line:84%
So, in other words, can we
make a stronger statement

00:42:02.070 --> 00:42:05.550 align:middle line:84%
than what Markov tells
us out of the 10,

00:42:05.550 --> 00:42:08.790 align:middle line:84%
just with the information
that we have the mean

00:42:08.790 --> 00:42:10.940 align:middle line:84%
and, we have a non-negative
random variable?

00:42:10.940 --> 00:42:13.663 align:middle line:90%


00:42:13.663 --> 00:42:15.455 align:middle line:84%
Is there anything
stronger that we can say?

00:42:15.455 --> 00:42:18.270 align:middle line:90%


00:42:18.270 --> 00:42:19.025 align:middle line:90%
Who thinks yes?

00:42:19.025 --> 00:42:21.840 align:middle line:90%


00:42:21.840 --> 00:42:23.080 align:middle line:90%
A couple of tentative hands.

00:42:23.080 --> 00:42:26.010 align:middle line:90%
Who thinks no?

00:42:26.010 --> 00:42:28.090 align:middle line:84%
A couple of less
tentative hands.

00:42:28.090 --> 00:42:28.790 align:middle line:90%
Who has no idea?

00:42:28.790 --> 00:42:32.070 align:middle line:90%


00:42:32.070 --> 00:42:36.782 align:middle line:84%
Well, let's think about
some simple examples then.

00:42:36.782 --> 00:42:39.480 align:middle line:84%
So let's go back to the
cell phone check problem

00:42:39.480 --> 00:42:43.170 align:middle line:90%
from, what was it, last week?

00:42:43.170 --> 00:42:45.330 align:middle line:84%
Don't remember which of
the lectures last week.

00:42:45.330 --> 00:42:46.300 align:middle line:90%
Do you say Thursday?

00:42:46.300 --> 00:42:47.192 align:middle line:90%
Both?

00:42:47.192 --> 00:42:50.260 align:middle line:90%
Both, OK.

00:42:50.260 --> 00:42:55.260 align:middle line:84%
So if we consider the
Lazy Susan version,

00:42:55.260 --> 00:43:03.995 align:middle line:84%
and we let R be the number of
people who get their phone--

00:43:03.995 --> 00:43:09.750 align:middle line:90%


00:43:09.750 --> 00:43:21.000 align:middle line:84%
so this is the Lazy
Susan How could we

00:43:21.000 --> 00:43:24.873 align:middle line:84%
use Markov to bound the
probability that everybody

00:43:24.873 --> 00:43:25.790 align:middle line:90%
gets their phone back?

00:43:25.790 --> 00:43:33.030 align:middle line:90%


00:43:33.030 --> 00:43:36.470 align:middle line:84%
So if everybody gets their
phone back, that's R equals n.

00:43:36.470 --> 00:43:48.090 align:middle line:90%


00:43:48.090 --> 00:43:50.470 align:middle line:84%
What does Markov tell us
about this probability?

00:43:50.470 --> 00:44:04.140 align:middle line:90%


00:44:04.140 --> 00:44:04.830 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:44:04.830 --> 00:44:06.083 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: At most, 1 over n.

00:44:06.083 --> 00:44:08.000 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Yeah,
it's at most, 1 over n.

00:44:08.000 --> 00:44:12.600 align:middle line:90%


00:44:12.600 --> 00:44:13.600 align:middle line:90%
Why is that?

00:44:13.600 --> 00:44:17.730 align:middle line:84%
Well, the expectation of R
is 1, as we saw last week.

00:44:17.730 --> 00:44:21.390 align:middle line:90%
The bound we're looking at is n.

00:44:21.390 --> 00:44:24.180 align:middle line:84%
So there's at most,
a 1 in n probability

00:44:24.180 --> 00:44:26.745 align:middle line:84%
that everybody gets
their phone back.

00:44:26.745 --> 00:44:28.620 align:middle line:84%
What is the actual
probability that everybody

00:44:28.620 --> 00:44:29.537 align:middle line:90%
gets their phone back?

00:44:29.537 --> 00:44:35.370 align:middle line:90%


00:44:35.370 --> 00:44:36.090 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:44:36.090 --> 00:44:37.043 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: 1 over n.

00:44:37.043 --> 00:44:37.960 align:middle line:90%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Yeah.

00:44:37.960 --> 00:44:40.620 align:middle line:84%
The actual probability
is 1 over n.

00:44:40.620 --> 00:44:43.140 align:middle line:90%
So this is tight.

00:44:43.140 --> 00:44:45.480 align:middle line:84%
We can't say anything
stronger than Markov

00:44:45.480 --> 00:44:47.230 align:middle line:90%
without additional information.

00:44:47.230 --> 00:44:50.490 align:middle line:90%


00:44:50.490 --> 00:44:51.770 align:middle line:90%
Does that make sense?

00:44:51.770 --> 00:44:54.753 align:middle line:90%


00:44:54.753 --> 00:44:56.920 align:middle line:84%
So if we know something
else about our distribution,

00:44:56.920 --> 00:44:58.753 align:middle line:84%
then we might be able
to say something more.

00:44:58.753 --> 00:45:01.230 align:middle line:84%
But if all we know
is the expectation

00:45:01.230 --> 00:45:04.430 align:middle line:84%
and the non-negativity,
then Markov

00:45:04.430 --> 00:45:05.555 align:middle line:90%
is the best that we can do.

00:45:05.555 --> 00:45:12.550 align:middle line:90%


00:45:12.550 --> 00:45:15.990 align:middle line:84%
On the other hand, suppose we're
permuting all of the phones

00:45:15.990 --> 00:45:17.855 align:middle line:84%
instead of putting
them on the Lazy Susan.

00:45:17.855 --> 00:45:35.520 align:middle line:90%


00:45:35.520 --> 00:45:37.047 align:middle line:84%
So in this case,
what does Markov

00:45:37.047 --> 00:45:38.880 align:middle line:84%
tell us about the
probability that everybody

00:45:38.880 --> 00:45:41.395 align:middle line:90%
gets their phone back?

00:45:41.395 --> 00:45:45.120 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:45:45.120 --> 00:45:47.700 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Well,
it's still 1 over n.

00:45:47.700 --> 00:45:50.580 align:middle line:84%
We've still got a
non-negative random variable

00:45:50.580 --> 00:45:51.640 align:middle line:90%
with the same mean.

00:45:51.640 --> 00:45:54.088 align:middle line:84%
We're still looking
at the same threshold.

00:45:54.088 --> 00:45:55.505 align:middle line:84%
So Markov gives
us the same bound.

00:45:55.505 --> 00:46:06.695 align:middle line:90%


00:46:06.695 --> 00:46:08.688 align:middle line:84%
What is the actual
probability that everybody

00:46:08.688 --> 00:46:09.605 align:middle line:90%
gets their phone back?

00:46:09.605 --> 00:46:27.660 align:middle line:90%


00:46:27.660 --> 00:46:31.360 align:middle line:84%
Well, that's exactly when you
have the identity permutation.

00:46:31.360 --> 00:46:33.490 align:middle line:84%
You've got n factorial
possible permutations.

00:46:33.490 --> 00:46:36.150 align:middle line:84%
One of them gives
everybody's phone back.

00:46:36.150 --> 00:46:41.770 align:middle line:84%
So what we're looking for is
actually 1 over n factorial.

00:46:41.770 --> 00:46:45.575 align:middle line:84%
So Markov is very much
not tight in this example.

00:46:45.575 --> 00:47:01.120 align:middle line:90%


00:47:01.120 --> 00:47:03.060 align:middle line:84%
So the next question
is, what can we

00:47:03.060 --> 00:47:06.420 align:middle line:84%
say if we do have
more information

00:47:06.420 --> 00:47:11.615 align:middle line:90%
about a random variable?

00:47:11.615 --> 00:47:18.030 align:middle line:90%


00:47:18.030 --> 00:47:21.450 align:middle line:84%
So, suppose we
know the variance.

00:47:21.450 --> 00:47:25.620 align:middle line:84%
So the variance of those two
distributions is very different.

00:47:25.620 --> 00:47:28.530 align:middle line:84%
In the case where we put the
phones on the Lazy Susan,

00:47:28.530 --> 00:47:30.412 align:middle line:90%
we've got a very high variance.

00:47:30.412 --> 00:47:32.370 align:middle line:84%
In the case where we have
a random permutation,

00:47:32.370 --> 00:47:34.830 align:middle line:90%
it's much lower.

00:47:34.830 --> 00:47:36.930 align:middle line:84%
So maybe the
variance can tell us

00:47:36.930 --> 00:47:40.990 align:middle line:90%
more about these probabilities.

00:47:40.990 --> 00:47:50.350 align:middle line:90%


00:47:50.350 --> 00:47:54.236 align:middle line:84%
So this is a different tail
bound, due to Chebyshev.

00:47:54.236 --> 00:47:58.200 align:middle line:90%


00:47:58.200 --> 00:48:08.400 align:middle line:84%
So probability that R
minus the expectation of R,

00:48:08.400 --> 00:48:13.110 align:middle line:84%
an absolute value
is at least x, is

00:48:13.110 --> 00:48:14.640 align:middle line:84%
less than or equal
to the variance

00:48:14.640 --> 00:48:19.640 align:middle line:90%
of x divided by x squared.

00:48:19.640 --> 00:48:29.586 align:middle line:90%


00:48:29.586 --> 00:48:33.240 align:middle line:84%
So note that we no longer
require non-negativity here.

00:48:33.240 --> 00:48:37.830 align:middle line:84%
We just require information
about the variance

00:48:37.830 --> 00:48:41.280 align:middle line:84%
And, well, we have to compute
it relative to the mean.

00:48:41.280 --> 00:48:46.120 align:middle line:90%


00:48:46.120 --> 00:48:49.040 align:middle line:84%
But R can be any
random variable.

00:48:49.040 --> 00:48:52.580 align:middle line:84%
We're no longer constrained to
looking at non-negative ones.

00:48:52.580 --> 00:48:53.660 align:middle line:90%
It can be anything.

00:48:53.660 --> 00:48:55.202 align:middle line:84%
We just have to
compute the variance.

00:48:55.202 --> 00:48:58.180 align:middle line:90%


00:48:58.180 --> 00:49:00.560 align:middle line:84%
How might we prove
Chebyshev's inequality?

00:49:00.560 --> 00:49:12.040 align:middle line:90%


00:49:12.040 --> 00:49:12.840 align:middle line:90%
Any ideas?

00:49:12.840 --> 00:49:20.200 align:middle line:90%


00:49:20.200 --> 00:49:22.420 align:middle line:90%
Is that a hand or a stretch?

00:49:22.420 --> 00:49:23.717 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:49:23.717 --> 00:49:25.180 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] Markov?

00:49:25.180 --> 00:49:26.330 align:middle line:90%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Yeah.

00:49:26.330 --> 00:49:29.890 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to prove
Chebyshev using Markov.

00:49:29.890 --> 00:49:40.900 align:middle line:84%
So in order to use
Markov, what do we need?

00:49:40.900 --> 00:49:43.120 align:middle line:84%
Well, we need a non-negative
random variable.

00:49:43.120 --> 00:49:47.500 align:middle line:84%
So similar to what
we were doing earlier

00:49:47.500 --> 00:49:49.810 align:middle line:84%
with shifting our
random variable,

00:49:49.810 --> 00:49:52.990 align:middle line:84%
we're going to define a new
random variable that we can then

00:49:52.990 --> 00:49:54.610 align:middle line:90%
apply Markov to.

00:49:54.610 --> 00:49:57.690 align:middle line:84%
And that should give
us this result here.

00:49:57.690 --> 00:50:05.176 align:middle line:90%


00:50:05.176 --> 00:50:08.500 align:middle line:84%
Does that make
sense to everybody?

00:50:08.500 --> 00:50:09.340 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:50:09.340 --> 00:50:13.458 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: For a [INAUDIBLE] is
variance of x supposed to be R?

00:50:13.458 --> 00:50:15.250 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Oh,
variance of R-- sorry.

00:50:15.250 --> 00:50:17.920 align:middle line:90%
Thank you.

00:50:17.920 --> 00:50:20.363 align:middle line:84%
Yes, variance of x does
not make any sense.

00:50:20.363 --> 00:50:30.322 align:middle line:90%


00:50:30.322 --> 00:50:32.380 align:middle line:84%
So what might be a
useful random variable

00:50:32.380 --> 00:50:33.585 align:middle line:90%
that we can apply Markov to?

00:50:33.585 --> 00:50:46.736 align:middle line:90%


00:50:46.736 --> 00:50:48.403 align:middle line:84%
Well, maybe here's
the way we can cheat.

00:50:48.403 --> 00:50:52.480 align:middle line:90%


00:50:52.480 --> 00:50:55.575 align:middle line:84%
In Markov's inequality,
what's the bound that we get?

00:50:55.575 --> 00:50:59.050 align:middle line:90%


00:50:59.050 --> 00:51:00.580 align:middle line:84%
The bound should
be the expectation

00:51:00.580 --> 00:51:01.455 align:middle line:90%
of a random variable.

00:51:01.455 --> 00:51:04.020 align:middle line:90%


00:51:04.020 --> 00:51:07.390 align:middle line:84%
So can we define a random
variable whose expectation

00:51:07.390 --> 00:51:08.835 align:middle line:90%
is the variance of R?

00:51:08.835 --> 00:51:11.950 align:middle line:90%


00:51:11.950 --> 00:51:13.108 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:51:13.108 --> 00:51:15.100 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:51:15.100 --> 00:51:17.110 align:middle line:90%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Yeah, exactly.

00:51:17.110 --> 00:51:24.330 align:middle line:84%
So R prime equals R minus
its expectation squared.

00:51:24.330 --> 00:51:28.340 align:middle line:90%


00:51:28.340 --> 00:51:30.650 align:middle line:90%
So this is non-negative.

00:51:30.650 --> 00:51:32.115 align:middle line:90%
It's a square of some value.

00:51:32.115 --> 00:51:35.140 align:middle line:90%


00:51:35.140 --> 00:51:41.740 align:middle line:84%
Its expectation by definition
is the variance of R.

00:51:41.740 --> 00:51:48.880 align:middle line:84%
And also, if we squint,
we can fiddle around

00:51:48.880 --> 00:51:52.270 align:middle line:84%
with this to
actually threshold R

00:51:52.270 --> 00:51:56.380 align:middle line:84%
prime instead of this absolute
value thing that we've got here.

00:51:56.380 --> 00:51:58.990 align:middle line:90%
How do we do that?

00:51:58.990 --> 00:52:01.550 align:middle line:84%
Well, we just square the
stuff in the absolute value.

00:52:01.550 --> 00:52:05.390 align:middle line:84%
It has the same square as if we
didn't have the absolute value.

00:52:05.390 --> 00:52:13.420 align:middle line:84%
So the probability that R minus
its expectation greater than

00:52:13.420 --> 00:52:17.650 align:middle line:84%
or equal to x equals
the probability

00:52:17.650 --> 00:52:23.260 align:middle line:84%
that R prime is greater
than or equal to x squared--

00:52:23.260 --> 00:52:27.320 align:middle line:84%
because those are
exactly the same event.

00:52:27.320 --> 00:52:31.480 align:middle line:84%
They're the same event, so
they have the same probability.

00:52:31.480 --> 00:52:35.110 align:middle line:84%
And now this looks like
something we can apply Markov,

00:52:35.110 --> 00:52:38.980 align:middle line:84%
less than or equal to
the expectation of R

00:52:38.980 --> 00:52:43.815 align:middle line:90%
prime divided by x squared.

00:52:43.815 --> 00:52:52.660 align:middle line:90%


00:52:52.660 --> 00:52:55.550 align:middle line:84%
Does that make
sense to everybody?

00:52:55.550 --> 00:53:10.540 align:middle line:90%


00:53:10.540 --> 00:53:12.133 align:middle line:84%
So let's take a
look at an example.

00:53:12.133 --> 00:53:19.000 align:middle line:90%


00:53:19.000 --> 00:53:22.120 align:middle line:84%
So let's look at those
test scores again.

00:53:22.120 --> 00:53:25.290 align:middle line:90%
Oops, sorry, my bad.

00:53:25.290 --> 00:53:38.680 align:middle line:90%


00:53:38.680 --> 00:53:41.713 align:middle line:84%
So R, same deal,
we've got test scores.

00:53:41.713 --> 00:53:45.550 align:middle line:90%


00:53:45.550 --> 00:53:49.990 align:middle line:84%
Expectation is--
what did we have?

00:53:49.990 --> 00:53:51.675 align:middle line:90%
70, 75?

00:53:51.675 --> 00:53:52.175 align:middle line:90%
75.

00:53:52.175 --> 00:53:55.450 align:middle line:90%


00:53:55.450 --> 00:53:57.083 align:middle line:90%
And say that the variance.

00:53:57.083 --> 00:54:00.220 align:middle line:90%


00:54:00.220 --> 00:54:01.380 align:middle line:90%
Is 25.

00:54:01.380 --> 00:54:06.106 align:middle line:90%


00:54:06.106 --> 00:54:10.510 align:middle line:84%
So now what can we say
about the probability

00:54:10.510 --> 00:54:14.263 align:middle line:90%
that R is at most, 65?

00:54:14.263 --> 00:54:22.030 align:middle line:90%


00:54:22.030 --> 00:54:22.860 align:middle line:90%
Any ideas?

00:54:22.860 --> 00:54:26.935 align:middle line:90%


00:54:26.935 --> 00:54:28.620 align:middle line:84%
How could we apply
Chebyshev to this?

00:54:28.620 --> 00:54:51.868 align:middle line:90%


00:54:51.868 --> 00:54:54.285 align:middle line:84%
That doesn't quite look like
the theorem statement, right?

00:54:54.285 --> 00:54:59.540 align:middle line:90%


00:54:59.540 --> 00:55:06.050 align:middle line:84%
But we can observe that this
is at most, the probability

00:55:06.050 --> 00:55:13.803 align:middle line:84%
that R is at most, 65, or R is
greater than or equal to 85.

00:55:13.803 --> 00:55:20.460 align:middle line:90%


00:55:20.460 --> 00:55:23.960 align:middle line:84%
If we take the
union of two events,

00:55:23.960 --> 00:55:27.200 align:middle line:84%
that union has at least
the probability of one

00:55:27.200 --> 00:55:30.140 align:middle line:90%
of those two constituent events.

00:55:30.140 --> 00:55:32.270 align:middle line:84%
So this is only increasing
the probability,

00:55:32.270 --> 00:55:39.550 align:middle line:84%
if we add in this extra
half of the event.

00:55:39.550 --> 00:55:49.200 align:middle line:90%


00:55:49.200 --> 00:55:51.420 align:middle line:84%
And what do we know
about this probability?

00:55:51.420 --> 00:55:55.040 align:middle line:90%


00:55:55.040 --> 00:55:57.205 align:middle line:84%
How could we rewrite
that in a nicer way?

00:55:57.205 --> 00:56:04.190 align:middle line:90%


00:56:04.190 --> 00:56:05.345 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:56:05.345 --> 00:56:06.720 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Probability
of actually

00:56:06.720 --> 00:56:10.430 align:middle line:84%
having [INAUDIBLE] expectation
is greater than or equal to 10.

00:56:10.430 --> 00:56:11.810 align:middle line:90%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Exactly.

00:56:11.810 --> 00:56:15.020 align:middle line:84%
So this is just saying
R deviates from its mean

00:56:15.020 --> 00:56:16.060 align:middle line:90%
by at least 10.

00:56:16.060 --> 00:56:30.365 align:middle line:90%


00:56:30.365 --> 00:56:34.370 align:middle line:84%
So now we've got it in the
form that Chebyshev likes.

00:56:34.370 --> 00:56:36.830 align:middle line:90%
So we can apply Chebyshev.

00:56:36.830 --> 00:56:42.453 align:middle line:84%
This is at most, variance
of R divided by--

00:56:42.453 --> 00:56:45.470 align:middle line:90%


00:56:45.470 --> 00:56:47.190 align:middle line:90%
R threshold is 10?

00:56:47.190 --> 00:56:48.115 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, 10 squared.

00:56:48.115 --> 00:57:00.980 align:middle line:90%


00:57:00.980 --> 00:57:05.005 align:middle line:90%
25 over 100 equals 1/4.

00:57:05.005 --> 00:57:11.330 align:middle line:90%


00:57:11.330 --> 00:57:17.990 align:middle line:84%
Now, we've got a much
stronger bound this time

00:57:17.990 --> 00:57:19.170 align:middle line:90%
than we did earlier.

00:57:19.170 --> 00:57:19.795 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, question?

00:57:19.795 --> 00:57:21.420 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Can you
explain one more time

00:57:21.420 --> 00:57:22.970 align:middle line:84%
how you got the
probability of R is

00:57:22.970 --> 00:57:27.290 align:middle line:84%
that [INAUDIBLE] 65 or greater
than 85 to the next probability?

00:57:27.290 --> 00:57:31.150 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Ah, OK,
so explain this equality?

00:57:31.150 --> 00:57:33.524 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:57:33.524 --> 00:57:35.780 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: So R
less than or equal to 65

00:57:35.780 --> 00:57:38.840 align:middle line:84%
or R greater than
or equal to 85,

00:57:38.840 --> 00:57:44.060 align:middle line:84%
we could rewrite
this as R minus--

00:57:44.060 --> 00:57:53.270 align:middle line:84%
well, R minus 75 is less
than or equal to negative 10.

00:57:53.270 --> 00:57:57.480 align:middle line:84%
And this one is R
minus 75 greater than

00:57:57.480 --> 00:57:58.480 align:middle line:90%
or equal to positive 10.

00:57:58.480 --> 00:58:01.430 align:middle line:90%


00:58:01.430 --> 00:58:06.530 align:middle line:84%
So if you absolute value both of
these, they're both greater than

00:58:06.530 --> 00:58:07.550 align:middle line:90%
or equal to 10.

00:58:07.550 --> 00:58:10.316 align:middle line:90%
Does that make sense?

00:58:10.316 --> 00:58:10.816 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:58:10.816 --> 00:58:13.938 align:middle line:90%


00:58:13.938 --> 00:58:17.275 align:middle line:84%
And other questions
about this example?

00:58:17.275 --> 00:58:26.600 align:middle line:90%


00:58:26.600 --> 00:58:31.950 align:middle line:84%
So because we have more
information than we had here,

00:58:31.950 --> 00:58:33.175 align:middle line:90%
we can get a stronger bound.

00:58:33.175 --> 00:58:35.840 align:middle line:90%


00:58:35.840 --> 00:58:37.510 align:middle line:84%
Knowing the variance
helps us out.

00:58:37.510 --> 00:58:46.940 align:middle line:90%


00:58:46.940 --> 00:58:50.570 align:middle line:84%
So equivalently,
we could rephrase

00:58:50.570 --> 00:58:56.840 align:middle line:84%
this in terms of
standard deviations.

00:58:56.840 --> 00:58:59.990 align:middle line:84%
Where would be a good
place to write this.

00:58:59.990 --> 00:59:01.970 align:middle line:90%
How about here?

00:59:01.970 --> 00:59:15.380 align:middle line:84%
So the probability of being at
least two standard deviations

00:59:15.380 --> 00:59:21.560 align:middle line:90%
from the mean is at most, 1/4.

00:59:21.560 --> 00:59:42.376 align:middle line:90%


00:59:42.376 --> 00:59:45.360 align:middle line:84%
Does anybody have any objections
to that last statement?

00:59:45.360 --> 01:00:10.010 align:middle line:90%


01:00:10.010 --> 01:00:12.340 align:middle line:84%
So if you've taken
a stats class,

01:00:12.340 --> 01:00:14.590 align:middle line:84%
you probably heard something
very different from that.

01:00:14.590 --> 01:00:19.700 align:middle line:90%


01:00:19.700 --> 01:00:20.630 align:middle line:90%
No?

01:00:20.630 --> 01:00:24.140 align:middle line:90%
Nobody's taking stats?

01:00:24.140 --> 01:00:24.810 align:middle line:90%
That's good.

01:00:24.810 --> 01:00:26.540 align:middle line:90%
High school stats is terrible.

01:00:26.540 --> 01:00:27.920 align:middle line:90%
Oh, that's on camera.

01:00:27.920 --> 01:00:28.710 align:middle line:90%
Never mind.

01:00:28.710 --> 01:00:30.020 align:middle line:90%
Stats are great.

01:00:30.020 --> 01:00:32.380 align:middle line:84%
it's good that you've saved
it for university instead

01:00:32.380 --> 01:00:33.505 align:middle line:90%
of doing it in high school.

01:00:33.505 --> 01:00:37.424 align:middle line:90%


01:00:37.424 --> 01:00:42.750 align:middle line:84%
So if you're looking at
a normal distribution,

01:00:42.750 --> 01:00:45.600 align:middle line:84%
you actually have a much
better bound than 1/4.

01:00:45.600 --> 01:00:47.680 align:middle line:84%
It's something
like a few percent.

01:00:47.680 --> 01:00:50.531 align:middle line:90%


01:00:50.531 --> 01:00:53.240 align:middle line:90%
So why is that.

01:00:53.240 --> 01:00:53.950 align:middle line:90%
Any ideas?

01:00:53.950 --> 01:01:00.410 align:middle line:90%


01:01:00.410 --> 01:01:02.270 align:middle line:84%
Well, for a normal
distribution, we

01:01:02.270 --> 01:01:09.544 align:middle line:84%
know a lot more about the random
variable than just its variance.

01:01:09.544 --> 01:01:12.320 align:middle line:84%
So if we know even more
about a random variable

01:01:12.320 --> 01:01:14.000 align:middle line:84%
than its variance,
it turns out we can

01:01:14.000 --> 01:01:18.110 align:middle line:90%
make even stronger statements.

01:01:18.110 --> 01:01:21.438 align:middle line:84%
Just like adding in the variance
was an upgrade from Markov,

01:01:21.438 --> 01:01:23.105 align:middle line:84%
let's see how we can
upgrade this again.

01:01:23.105 --> 01:01:35.140 align:middle line:90%


01:01:35.140 --> 01:01:36.120 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

01:01:36.120 --> 01:01:37.330 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN:
Yeah, what's up?

01:01:37.330 --> 01:01:38.640 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: What's a
normal distribution?

01:01:38.640 --> 01:01:40.980 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Oh, what's
a normal distribution?

01:01:40.980 --> 01:01:44.770 align:middle line:84%
Think of a normal distribution
as numb er of heads,

01:01:44.770 --> 01:01:46.920 align:middle line:84%
if you flip a whole
bunch of coins.

01:01:46.920 --> 01:01:51.150 align:middle line:84%
That's not quite it,
but roughly speaking--

01:01:51.150 --> 01:01:51.890 align:middle line:90%
good catch.

01:01:51.890 --> 01:02:15.365 align:middle line:90%


01:02:15.365 --> 01:02:19.200 align:middle line:84%
So as I just said, if you
flip a whole bunch of coins,

01:02:19.200 --> 01:02:23.705 align:middle line:84%
let your random variable
R be the number of heads.

01:02:23.705 --> 01:02:27.540 align:middle line:84%
You know a lot more about
this random variable

01:02:27.540 --> 01:02:29.870 align:middle line:90%
than just its variance.

01:02:29.870 --> 01:02:32.610 align:middle line:84%
You can decompose
your random variable

01:02:32.610 --> 01:02:37.570 align:middle line:84%
into a sum of a whole
bunch of indicators.

01:02:37.570 --> 01:02:40.210 align:middle line:84%
And all of those indicators
are mutually independent.

01:02:40.210 --> 01:02:45.726 align:middle line:90%


01:02:45.726 --> 01:02:49.620 align:middle line:84%
In order to use Chebyshev, you
don't need mutual independence.

01:02:49.620 --> 01:02:51.100 align:middle line:84%
If you had something
of that form,

01:02:51.100 --> 01:02:52.680 align:middle line:84%
you just need
pairwise independence.

01:02:52.680 --> 01:02:54.055 align:middle line:84%
You need to compute
the variance.

01:02:54.055 --> 01:02:56.475 align:middle line:90%


01:02:56.475 --> 01:02:59.183 align:middle line:84%
But if, on top of that, you
have mutual independence,

01:02:59.183 --> 01:03:00.725 align:middle line:84%
it turns out you
can do a lot better.

01:03:00.725 --> 01:03:03.620 align:middle line:90%


01:03:03.620 --> 01:03:32.070 align:middle line:84%
So suppose T1, T2, T3, up to
Tn are mutually independent

01:03:32.070 --> 01:03:33.930 align:middle line:90%
random variables.

01:03:33.930 --> 01:03:38.645 align:middle line:84%
And, well, let's say, in
addition, they are bounded.

01:03:38.645 --> 01:03:54.162 align:middle line:90%


01:03:54.162 --> 01:03:56.580 align:middle line:84%
And the random variable
we actually care about

01:03:56.580 --> 01:03:58.580 align:middle line:90%
is T, which is their sum.

01:03:58.580 --> 01:04:17.790 align:middle line:90%


01:04:17.790 --> 01:04:20.340 align:middle line:84%
Oh, and say we've also
got some threshold

01:04:20.340 --> 01:04:24.240 align:middle line:90%
C, which is at least 1.

01:04:24.240 --> 01:04:30.986 align:middle line:84%
The probability that T is at
least C times its expectation--

01:04:30.986 --> 01:04:36.970 align:middle line:90%


01:04:36.970 --> 01:04:39.480 align:middle line:90%
I'll close that as well--

01:04:39.480 --> 01:04:44.850 align:middle line:84%
less than or equal to
e to the negative C

01:04:44.850 --> 01:05:04.505 align:middle line:84%
log of C minus C plus 1
times the expectation of T.

01:05:04.505 --> 01:05:12.330 align:middle line:84%
So a little bit of
a mouthful, but what

01:05:12.330 --> 01:05:13.445 align:middle line:90%
exactly is going on here?

01:05:13.445 --> 01:05:23.220 align:middle line:90%


01:05:23.220 --> 01:05:29.940 align:middle line:84%
So basically, Markov was
saying that the probability

01:05:29.940 --> 01:05:34.320 align:middle line:84%
that you deviate from the
mean by a large amount,

01:05:34.320 --> 01:05:43.200 align:middle line:84%
it's at most linear in
how far you're deviating.

01:05:43.200 --> 01:05:46.350 align:middle line:84%
Chebyshev said it's
at most, quadratic.

01:05:46.350 --> 01:05:48.480 align:middle line:84%
This is saying it's
at most, exponential,

01:05:48.480 --> 01:05:51.510 align:middle line:90%
or inverse exponential.

01:05:51.510 --> 01:05:54.258 align:middle line:84%
So you have a much stronger
condition that gives you

01:05:54.258 --> 01:05:55.175 align:middle line:90%
a much stronger bound.

01:05:55.175 --> 01:05:59.480 align:middle line:90%


01:05:59.480 --> 01:06:00.905 align:middle line:90%
And how could we prove it?

01:06:00.905 --> 01:06:08.550 align:middle line:90%


01:06:08.550 --> 01:06:09.485 align:middle line:90%
Not like this.

01:06:09.485 --> 01:06:54.720 align:middle line:90%


01:06:54.720 --> 01:06:55.625 align:middle line:90%
Any ideas?

01:06:55.625 --> 01:07:12.420 align:middle line:90%


01:07:12.420 --> 01:07:14.410 align:middle line:90%
Well, maybe a proof sketch--

01:07:14.410 --> 01:07:16.005 align:middle line:84%
we won't go through
the entire proof.

01:07:16.005 --> 01:07:25.810 align:middle line:90%


01:07:25.810 --> 01:07:28.780 align:middle line:84%
So what tools do
we have already?

01:07:28.780 --> 01:07:30.120 align:middle line:90%
What might we be able to do?

01:07:30.120 --> 01:08:03.100 align:middle line:90%


01:08:03.100 --> 01:08:07.150 align:middle line:84%
Well, what happens
if we apply Markov?

01:08:07.150 --> 01:08:08.415 align:middle line:90%
How can we apply Markov?

01:08:08.415 --> 01:08:14.230 align:middle line:90%


01:08:14.230 --> 01:08:18.405 align:middle line:84%
In order to use Markov, we need
a non-negative random variable.

01:08:18.405 --> 01:08:24.069 align:middle line:90%


01:08:24.069 --> 01:08:27.250 align:middle line:84%
So in order to
prove Chebyshev, we

01:08:27.250 --> 01:08:31.300 align:middle line:84%
took a square that made
something non-negative.

01:08:31.300 --> 01:08:33.614 align:middle line:84%
What might be a reasonable
thing to try in this case?

01:08:33.614 --> 01:08:49.870 align:middle line:90%


01:08:49.870 --> 01:08:50.500 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:08:50.500 --> 01:08:51.760 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Add 1.

01:08:51.760 --> 01:08:54.250 align:middle line:90%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Add 1.

01:08:54.250 --> 01:08:59.429 align:middle line:84%
OK, so look at T
plus 1 instead of T?

01:08:59.429 --> 01:09:04.840 align:middle line:90%


01:09:04.840 --> 01:09:10.210 align:middle line:84%
So that's actually
not going to help us.

01:09:10.210 --> 01:09:12.430 align:middle line:84%
T is already the
sum of a bunch of

01:09:12.430 --> 01:09:14.540 align:middle line:90%
non-negative random variables.

01:09:14.540 --> 01:09:16.216 align:middle line:90%
So it's already non-negative.

01:09:16.216 --> 01:09:19.359 align:middle line:90%


01:09:19.359 --> 01:09:23.529 align:middle line:84%
We're not looking to turn
a non-negative-- or sorry,

01:09:23.529 --> 01:09:25.060 align:middle line:84%
turn an arbitrary
random variable

01:09:25.060 --> 01:09:26.649 align:middle line:90%
into a non-negative one.

01:09:26.649 --> 01:09:31.060 align:middle line:84%
We are trying to find a more
useful non-negative random

01:09:31.060 --> 01:09:33.040 align:middle line:90%
variable.

01:09:33.040 --> 01:09:35.859 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:09:35.859 --> 01:09:37.007 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:09:37.007 --> 01:09:38.165 align:middle line:90%
STUDENT: Log of both sides?

01:09:38.165 --> 01:09:40.040 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Take
the log of both sides--

01:09:40.040 --> 01:09:40.540 align:middle line:90%
close.

01:09:40.540 --> 01:10:01.960 align:middle line:90%


01:10:01.960 --> 01:10:03.446 align:middle line:90%
What happens if we exponentiate?

01:10:03.446 --> 01:10:06.910 align:middle line:90%


01:10:06.910 --> 01:10:14.360 align:middle line:84%
So take T prime
equals C to the T.

01:10:14.360 --> 01:10:47.020 align:middle line:90%


01:10:47.020 --> 01:10:48.405 align:middle line:90%
What do we know about T prime?

01:10:48.405 --> 01:11:29.740 align:middle line:90%


01:11:29.740 --> 01:11:33.010 align:middle line:84%
Well, we're taking something
that's at least 1, right?

01:11:33.010 --> 01:11:35.720 align:middle line:84%
We're raising it to
some positive power--

01:11:35.720 --> 01:11:37.260 align:middle line:90%
well, some non-negative power.

01:11:37.260 --> 01:11:47.844 align:middle line:90%


01:11:47.844 --> 01:11:49.980 align:middle line:84%
So T prime is a non-negative
random variable.

01:11:49.980 --> 01:11:56.170 align:middle line:90%


01:11:56.170 --> 01:11:57.675 align:middle line:84%
Do we know anything
more about it?

01:11:57.675 --> 01:12:11.830 align:middle line:90%


01:12:11.830 --> 01:12:12.330 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:12:12.330 --> 01:12:13.660 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: It's at least 1.

01:12:13.660 --> 01:12:16.750 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: It's
at least 1, yeah.

01:12:16.750 --> 01:12:18.750 align:middle line:84%
So maybe we try
applying Markov to this.

01:12:18.750 --> 01:12:25.010 align:middle line:90%


01:12:25.010 --> 01:12:26.590 align:middle line:84%
So now we've got
a random variable

01:12:26.590 --> 01:12:30.490 align:middle line:84%
that takes values in the
range from 0 to C to the n, C

01:12:30.490 --> 01:12:31.305 align:middle line:90%
to the n minus 1.

01:12:31.305 --> 01:12:35.690 align:middle line:90%


01:12:35.690 --> 01:12:39.910 align:middle line:84%
Now, how could we
rewrite this condition,

01:12:39.910 --> 01:12:45.940 align:middle line:84%
T greater than or equal to
C times expectation of T

01:12:45.940 --> 01:12:47.055 align:middle line:90%
in terms of T prime?

01:12:47.055 --> 01:13:12.640 align:middle line:90%


01:13:12.640 --> 01:13:19.270 align:middle line:84%
Well, because C is at least
1, exponentiation is monotone.

01:13:19.270 --> 01:13:23.620 align:middle line:84%
So this is the same as C to the
T greater than or equal to C

01:13:23.620 --> 01:13:54.680 align:middle line:84%
to the C times expectation of T.
And we don't have too much time.

01:13:54.680 --> 01:13:58.850 align:middle line:84%
So I think I will refer you to
the book, if you are interested.

01:13:58.850 --> 01:14:07.460 align:middle line:84%
But the main idea
is this step here.

01:14:07.460 --> 01:14:09.470 align:middle line:84%
You take the random
variable you care about,

01:14:09.470 --> 01:14:12.260 align:middle line:90%
and you exponentiate it.

01:14:12.260 --> 01:14:17.430 align:middle line:84%
And then if you
apply Markov to that,

01:14:17.430 --> 01:14:19.850 align:middle line:84%
it actually gives you
a much stronger bound.

01:14:19.850 --> 01:14:23.540 align:middle line:84%
If you're using the
mutual independence of all

01:14:23.540 --> 01:14:25.950 align:middle line:84%
of the component
random variables,

01:14:25.950 --> 01:14:28.430 align:middle line:84%
this will give you a much
stronger bound than even

01:14:28.430 --> 01:14:29.480 align:middle line:90%
Chernoff.

01:14:29.480 --> 01:14:33.800 align:middle line:84%
So I promised you
last week that we

01:14:33.800 --> 01:14:36.570 align:middle line:90%
would revisit the coin tosses.

01:14:36.570 --> 01:14:37.735 align:middle line:90%
So let's do that briefly.

01:14:37.735 --> 01:14:40.834 align:middle line:90%


01:14:40.834 --> 01:14:53.890 align:middle line:84%
So suppose R is the number
of heads if you flip n coins.

01:14:53.890 --> 01:15:05.690 align:middle line:90%


01:15:05.690 --> 01:15:10.040 align:middle line:84%
So if you recall, we were
looking at the probability

01:15:10.040 --> 01:15:17.800 align:middle line:84%
that R is equal to
n over 4 before.

01:15:17.800 --> 01:15:20.810 align:middle line:90%


01:15:20.810 --> 01:15:27.650 align:middle line:84%
Or maybe equivalently, 3n
over 4 might be a better way

01:15:27.650 --> 01:15:30.416 align:middle line:90%
to analogize.

01:15:30.416 --> 01:15:33.296 align:middle line:90%


01:15:33.296 --> 01:15:37.520 align:middle line:84%
And I promised you that we
would revisit this probability,

01:15:37.520 --> 01:15:39.775 align:middle line:84%
R greater than or
equal to 3n over 4.

01:15:39.775 --> 01:15:53.440 align:middle line:90%


01:15:53.440 --> 01:15:58.670 align:middle line:84%
Now, what happens if we apply
each of our three tail bounds

01:15:58.670 --> 01:15:59.380 align:middle line:90%
to R?

01:15:59.380 --> 01:16:11.717 align:middle line:90%


01:16:11.717 --> 01:16:13.300 align:middle line:84%
Well, first, what
happens with Markov?

01:16:13.300 --> 01:16:21.590 align:middle line:90%


01:16:21.590 --> 01:16:22.790 align:middle line:90%
So let's call this p.

01:16:22.790 --> 01:16:29.526 align:middle line:90%


01:16:29.526 --> 01:16:30.775 align:middle line:90%
p is at most, what?

01:16:30.775 --> 01:16:54.080 align:middle line:90%


01:16:54.080 --> 01:16:58.640 align:middle line:84%
Well, the probability that R
is at least some threshold,

01:16:58.640 --> 01:17:06.000 align:middle line:84%
it's going to be the expectation
of R divided by this threshold.

01:17:06.000 --> 01:17:09.260 align:middle line:90%


01:17:09.260 --> 01:17:11.470 align:middle line:84%
What's the expectation
of R? n over 2.

01:17:11.470 --> 01:17:19.832 align:middle line:90%


01:17:19.832 --> 01:17:21.280 align:middle line:90%
So this is going to be 2/3.

01:17:21.280 --> 01:17:26.390 align:middle line:90%


01:17:26.390 --> 01:17:27.570 align:middle line:90%
What about Chebyshev?

01:17:27.570 --> 01:17:43.550 align:middle line:90%


01:17:43.550 --> 01:17:48.890 align:middle line:84%
So, similar to what we did with
the first Chebyshev example,

01:17:48.890 --> 01:17:52.130 align:middle line:84%
p is going to be at
most, the probability

01:17:52.130 --> 01:17:57.890 align:middle line:84%
that R differs from its
expectation in either direction

01:17:57.890 --> 01:17:58.825 align:middle line:90%
by another 4.

01:17:58.825 --> 01:18:02.060 align:middle line:90%


01:18:02.060 --> 01:18:05.540 align:middle line:90%
So what does that give us?

01:18:05.540 --> 01:18:10.970 align:middle line:84%
Probability R minus,
let's say, n over

01:18:10.970 --> 01:18:18.500 align:middle line:84%
2 greater than or
equal to n over

01:18:18.500 --> 01:18:31.180 align:middle line:84%
4 is at most var of r
divided by n over 4 squared.

01:18:31.180 --> 01:18:40.370 align:middle line:90%


01:18:40.370 --> 01:18:42.130 align:middle line:90%
So what is the variance of R?

01:18:42.130 --> 01:18:55.868 align:middle line:90%


01:18:55.868 --> 01:18:56.785 align:middle line:90%
Does anybody remember?

01:18:56.785 --> 01:19:01.820 align:middle line:90%


01:19:01.820 --> 01:19:04.680 align:middle line:84%
We've got a sum of a
bunch of indicators.

01:19:04.680 --> 01:19:07.250 align:middle line:84%
They're all mutually
independent.

01:19:07.250 --> 01:19:10.070 align:middle line:90%
So the variance is linear.

01:19:10.070 --> 01:19:12.060 align:middle line:84%
What's the variance
of a single indicator?

01:19:12.060 --> 01:19:19.250 align:middle line:90%


01:19:19.250 --> 01:19:21.950 align:middle line:90%
Nobody?

01:19:21.950 --> 01:19:23.352 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:19:23.352 --> 01:19:24.650 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: It's n over 4.

01:19:24.650 --> 01:19:26.120 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN:
Yeah, n over 4--

01:19:26.120 --> 01:19:28.015 align:middle line:84%
well, for R, not
for a single one.

01:19:28.015 --> 01:19:31.930 align:middle line:90%


01:19:31.930 --> 01:19:38.060 align:middle line:84%
So n over 4 divided by n
squared over 16 equals 4 over n.

01:19:38.060 --> 01:19:41.000 align:middle line:90%


01:19:41.000 --> 01:19:45.997 align:middle line:84%
So, much better, much better
than the 2/3 we just got.

01:19:45.997 --> 01:19:47.330 align:middle line:90%
What happens if we use Chernoff?

01:19:47.330 --> 01:20:13.840 align:middle line:90%


01:20:13.840 --> 01:20:15.600 align:middle line:90%
Any ideas?

01:20:15.600 --> 01:20:16.380 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:20:16.380 --> 01:20:18.780 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Plug in 3/2 for C.

01:20:18.780 --> 01:20:23.725 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Plug in
3/2 for C. So C equals 3/2.

01:20:23.725 --> 01:20:24.225 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:20:24.225 --> 01:20:33.120 align:middle line:90%


01:20:33.120 --> 01:20:35.240 align:middle line:84%
Why don't I put
Chernoff back up here.

01:20:35.240 --> 01:20:49.206 align:middle line:90%


01:20:49.206 --> 01:20:50.980 align:middle line:90%
and what does that give us?

01:20:50.980 --> 01:21:03.720 align:middle line:84%
Probability that R is at least
3/2 times expectation of R is

01:21:03.720 --> 01:21:14.950 align:middle line:84%
less than or equal to e to the
minus C log C minus C plus 1.

01:21:14.950 --> 01:21:19.620 align:middle line:84%
So this is a constant
times the expectation

01:21:19.620 --> 01:21:27.660 align:middle line:84%
of R. So the expectation
of R is n over 2.

01:21:27.660 --> 01:21:29.260 align:middle line:90%
This is a constant.

01:21:29.260 --> 01:21:31.380 align:middle line:84%
So we've got something
that's exponential,

01:21:31.380 --> 01:21:33.020 align:middle line:90%
or inverse exponential, in n--

01:21:33.020 --> 01:21:37.170 align:middle line:90%


01:21:37.170 --> 01:21:45.425 align:middle line:84%
oops-- e to the
minus order of n.

01:21:45.425 --> 01:21:52.173 align:middle line:90%


01:21:52.173 --> 01:21:59.130 align:middle line:84%
So, Markov gave us a really
bad bound; Chebyshev, linear--

01:21:59.130 --> 01:22:00.750 align:middle line:90%
pretty reasonable.

01:22:00.750 --> 01:22:03.760 align:middle line:84%
Chernoff gives us
an exponential.

01:22:03.760 --> 01:22:05.620 align:middle line:84%
So that's all we
have time for today.

01:22:05.620 --> 01:22:07.530 align:middle line:84%
Sorry, I went a
little bit over time.

01:22:07.530 --> 01:22:10.470 align:middle line:84%
It's been a pleasure teaching
you all this semester.

01:22:10.470 --> 01:22:14.190 align:middle line:84%
And let's see, we have the
rest of our instructors

01:22:14.190 --> 01:22:15.610 align:middle line:90%
and at least one TA.

01:22:15.610 --> 01:22:17.640 align:middle line:90%
Hello, Lily.

01:22:17.640 --> 01:22:21.420 align:middle line:84%
If anything went wrong, it was
probably my fault. Anything

01:22:21.420 --> 01:22:24.840 align:middle line:84%
that went right, you have
your TAs to thank for it,

01:22:24.840 --> 01:22:25.890 align:middle line:90%
including Lily.

01:22:25.890 --> 01:22:28.750 align:middle line:90%
Lily's amazing.

01:22:28.750 --> 01:22:33.870 align:middle line:84%
Perhaps I will see some of
you next term in 6.1210.

01:22:33.870 --> 01:22:34.990 align:middle line:90%
Good luck on the final.

01:22:34.990 --> 01:22:36.910 align:middle line:84%
Make sure you take
the right one.

01:22:36.910 --> 01:22:39.160 align:middle line:84%
ERIK DEMAINE: Thanks for
being students in this class.

01:22:39.160 --> 01:22:40.077 align:middle line:90%
It's been lots of fun.

01:22:40.077 --> 01:22:41.560 align:middle line:90%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Yeah.

01:22:41.560 --> 01:22:44.610 align:middle line:90%
[APPLAUSE]

01:22:44.610 --> 01:22:50.000 align:middle line:90%